# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: big-science
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] A graduate of the University of Chicago, which awarded him his doctorate in mathematical biophysics in 1939, Weinberg joined the Manhattan Project's Metallurgical Laboratory in September 1941.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The following year he became part of Eugene Wigner's Theoretical Group, whose task was to design the nuclear reactors that would convert uranium into plutonium.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg replaced Wigner as director of research at ORNL in 1948, and became director of the laboratory in 1955.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In 1960, Weinberg was appointed to the President's Science Advisory Committee in the Eisenhower administration and later served on it in the Kennedy administration.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] After leaving the ORNL in 1973, he was named director of the Office of Energy Research and Development in Washington, D.C., in 1974.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The following year he founded and became the first director of the Institute for Energy Analysis at Oak Ridge Associated Universities (ORAU).
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Alvin Martin Weinberg was born April 20, 1915, in Chicago, Illinois, the son of Jacob Weinberg and Emma Levinson Weinberg, two Russian Jewish emigrants who met in 1905 on board the boat carrying them to the United States.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He had an older sister, Fay Goleman, who was born on November 30, 1910.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] She later became a sociology professor at the University of the Pacific, and was the mother of Daniel Goleman.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He attended Theodore Roosevelt High School in Chicago.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg entered the University of Chicago, from which he received his Bachelor of Science (B.S.) degree in physics in 1935, and his Master of Science (M.S.) in physics the following year.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He received his Ph.D. from the University of Chicago in mathematical biophysics in 1939, writing his thesis on *Mathematical foundations for a theory of biophysical periodicity*, under the supervision of Carl Eckart.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg later lamented that, in restricting his thesis to linear systems, he had overlooked interesting nonlinear systems that Ilya Prigogine later received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for studying.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] While at Chicago, Weinberg was hired by the family of Margaret Despres, a student at the University of Chicago, to tutor her in mathematics.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] They had two sons, David Robert Weinberg and Richard J.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg taught courses at Wright Junior College.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He applied for and received a National Research Council fellowship to study under Kenneth S.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Cole at Columbia University, but never took it up, as Cole came to Chicago to work on the Manhattan Project as a radiation biologist.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg was recruited to work at its Metallurgical Laboratory at the University of Chicago in September 1941 by Eckart and Samuel Allison, who needed someone to work on the latter's neutron capture calculations.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In early 1942, Arthur Compton concentrated the Manhattan Project's various teams working on plutonium at the University of Chicago.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] This brought in many top scientists including Herbert Anderson, Bernard Feld, Enrico Fermi, Leó Szilárd and Walter Zinn from Columbia, and Edward Creutz, Gilbert Plass, Eugene Wigner and John Wheeler from Princeton University.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Wigner led the Theoretical Group at the Metallurgical Laboratory that included Alvin Weinberg, Katharine Way, Gale Young and Edward Creutz.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The group's task was to design the production nuclear reactors that would convert uranium into plutonium.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] At the time, reactors existed only on paper, and no reactor had yet gone critical.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In July 1942, Wigner chose a conservative 100 MW design, with a graphite neutron moderator and water cooling.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The choice of water as a coolant was controversial at the time.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Water was known to absorb neutrons, thereby reducing the efficiency of the reactor, but Wigner was confident that his group's calculations were correct and that water would work, while the technical difficulties involved in using helium or liquid metal as coolants would delay the project.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] After the United States Army Corps of Engineers took over the Manhattan Project, it gave responsibility for the detailed design and construction of the reactors to DuPont.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] There was friction between the company and Wigner and his team.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Major differences between Wigner's reactor design and DuPont's included increasing the number of process tubes from 1,500 in a circular array to 2,004 in a square array, and cutting the power from 500 MW to 250 MW.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] As it turned out, the design decision by DuPont to give the reactor additional tubes came in handy when neutron poisoning became a problem for the B Reactor at the Hanford Site.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The extra tubes allowed a greater fuel load to overcome the poisoning.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Without them the reactor would have had to be run at low power until enough of the boron impurities in the graphite had been burned up to allow it to reach full power, which would have delayed full operation by up to a year.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] As the reactors at Hanford came online, the Metallurgical Laboratory turned its attention back to theoretical designs.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The discovery of spontaneous fission in reactor-bred plutonium due to contamination by plutonium-240 led Wigner to propose switching to breeding uranium-233 from thorium, but the challenge was met by the Los Alamos Laboratory developing an implosion-type nuclear weapon design.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Wigner was also intrigued by the possibility of doing away with much of the complexities of a reactor by having the uranium in solution or a slurry in heavy water.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The Metallurgical Laboratory attempted to find a way of doing this.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Amongst the competing designs, Weinberg proposed the pressurized water reactor, which ultimately became the most common design.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] This was only one of the many possibilities discussed by Weinberg and his colleagues at Chicago and Oak Ridge.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The ultimate success of the pressurized water reactor, he wrote, was due less to any superior characteristics of water, but rather to the decision to power the prototype of the Mark I submarine thermal reactor with a pressurized version of the Materials Testing Reactor at Oak Ridge.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Once pressurized water was established, other possibilities became too expensive to pursue, but Weinberg remained interested in other possibilities.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] According to Freeman Dyson, he was the only nuclear pioneer who supported the wide universe of reactor designs.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In 1945, Wigner accepted a position as the director of research at the Clinton Laboratories in Oak Ridge, Tennessee, which then had a staff of about 800.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He took with him his protégés Gale Young, Katherine Way and Weinberg.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg, who was the first to arrive at Oak Ridge in May 1945, became head of the Physics Division in 1946.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] But after the Atomic Energy Commission took over responsibility for the laboratory's operations from the Manhattan Project at the start of 1947, Wigner, feeling unsuited to a managerial role in the new environment, left Oak Ridge at the end of summer in 1947 and returned to Princeton University.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The administration of the Clinton Laboratories passed from Monsanto to the University of Chicago in May 1947, and then to Union Carbide in December 1947.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The Atomic Energy Commission's influential General Advisory Committee, chaired by J.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Robert Oppenheimer, recommended that all work on reactors be concentrated at the Argonne National Laboratory, the successor to the Metallurgical Laboratory, near Chicago.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] There was also competition for staff and resources from the newly established Brookhaven National Laboratory near New York.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Morale was low, and no one could be found to take on the job of director of research at the laboratory, renamed the Oak Ridge National Laboratory (ORNL) in January 1948.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] At least six people turned down the job before Union Carbide's acting Director, Nelson (Bunny) Rucker, asked Weinberg to become director of research in March 1948.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg was subsequently appointed director in 1955.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He often sat in the front row at ORNL division information meetings and he would ask the first, often very penetrating, question after each scientific talk.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] For young scientists giving their first presentation, the experience could be frightening, but it was also exciting and stimulating.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The Aircraft Nuclear Propulsion (ANP) project was ORNL's biggest program, using 25% of ORNL's budget.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The ANP project's military goal was to produce a nuclear-powered aircraft (a bomber) to overcome the range limitations of jet-fueled aircraft at that time.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] That the project had little chance of success was not overlooked, but it provided employment and allowed ORNL to stay in the reactor development business.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] ORNL successfully built and operated a prototype of an aircraft reactor power plant by creating the world's first molten salt fueled and cooled reactor called the Aircraft Reactor Experiment (ARE) in 1954, which set a record high temperature of operation of 1,600 °F (870 °C).
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Due to the radiation hazard posed to aircrew, and people on the ground in the event of a crash, new developments in ballistic missile technology, aerial refueling and longer range jet bombers, President Kennedy canceled the program in June 1961.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg had the Materials Testing Reactor converted into a mock-up of a real reactor called the Low Intensity Test Reactor (LITR) or "Poor Man's Pile".
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Experiments at the LITR led to the design of both pressurized water reactors (PWRs) and boiling water reactors (BWRs), which have since become the dominant reactor types in commercial nuclear power plants.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg was attracted to the simplicity and self-controlling features of nuclear reactors that used fluid fuels, such as Harold Urey and Eugene Wigner's proposed Aqueous Homogeneous Reactor.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Therefore, to support the Nuclear Aircraft project in the late 1940s, Weinberg asked ORNL's reactor engineers to design a reactor using liquid instead of solid fuel.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] This Homogeneous Reactor Experiment (HRE) was affectionately dubbed "Alvin's 3P reactor" because it required a pot, a pipe, and a pump.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The HRE went into operation in 1950 and, at the criticality party, Weinberg brought the appropriate spirits: "When piles go critical in Chicago, we celebrate with wine.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] When piles go critical in Tennessee, we celebrate with Jack Daniel's." The HRE operated for 105 days before it was closed down.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Despite its leaks and corrosion, valuable information was gained from its operation and it proved a simple and safe reactor to control.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] During the time the HRE was online, Senators John F.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Kennedy and Albert Gore, Sr. visited ORNL and were hosted by Weinberg.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Under Weinberg, ORNL shifted its focus to a civilian version of the meltdown-proof Molten Salt Reactor (MSR) away from the military's "daft" idea of nuclear-powered aircraft.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The Molten-Salt Reactor Experiment (MSRE) set a record for continuous operation and was the first to use Thorium irradiated to produce uranium-233 as fuel.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] It also used plutonium-239 and the standard, naturally occurring uranium-235.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The MSR also afforded the opportunity to change the chemistry of the molten salt while the reactor was operating to remove fission products and add new fuel or change the fuel, all of which is called "online processing".
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Under Weinberg's tenure as director, ORNL's Biology Division grew to five times the size of the next largest division.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] This division was charged with understanding how ionizing radiation interacts with living things and to try to find ways to help them survive radiation damage, such as bone marrow transplants.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In the 1960s Weinberg also pursued new missions for ORNL, such as using nuclear energy to desalinate seawater.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He recruited Philip Hammond from the Los Alamos National Laboratory to further this mission and in 1970 started the first big ecology project in the United States: the National Science Foundation – Research Applied to National Needs Environmental Program.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In 1958, Weinberg coauthored the first nuclear reactor textbook, *The Physical Theory of Neutron Chain Reactors*, with Wigner.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The following year, 1959, he was elected president of the American Nuclear Society and, in 1960, began service on the President's Science Advisory Committee under the Eisenhower and Kennedy administrations.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Starting in 1945 with Patent #2,736,696, Weinberg, usually with Wigner, filed numerous patents on the light water reactor (LWR) technology that has provided the United States' primary nuclear reactors.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The main LWR types are Pressurized Water Reactors (PWRs) and Boiling Water Reactors (BWRs), that serve in Naval propulsion and commercial nuclear power.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In 1965 he was appointed vice president of Union Carbide's Nuclear Division.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg's firing effectively halted development of the MSR, as it was virtually unknown by other nuclear laboratories and specialists.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg was named director of the Office of Energy Research and Development in Washington, D.C., in 1974.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The following year he founded and became the first director of Institute for Energy Analysis at Oak Ridge Associated Universities (ORAU).
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] This institute focused on evaluating alternatives for meeting future energy requirements.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] From 1976 to 1984, the Institute for Energy Analysis was a center for study of diverse issues related to carbon dioxide and global warming.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He worked at ORAU until retiring to become an ORAU distinguished fellow in 1985.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In June, 1977, Weinberg testified at a congressional hearing of the House Subcommittee on the Environment and the Atmosphere concerning the impact of increasing carbon dioxide emissions on global average temperatures.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He stated that a doubling of global carbon dioxide emissions by 2025, which some scientists predicted would occur, would lead to a two-degree Celsius increase in global average temperature.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] In 1992 he was named chairman of the International Friendship Bell Committee, which arranged for the installation of a Japanese bell in Oak Ridge.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He also called for strengthening of the International Atomic Energy Agency and systems to defend against nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He later married a stock broker, Genevieve DePersio, who died in 2004.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] Weinberg died at his home in Oak Ridge on October 18, 2006.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] He was survived by his other son, Richard, and sister Fay Goleman.
[src:big-science/alvin-m-weinberg] The Alvin Weinberg Foundation is named for him.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A **nuclear weapon** is an explosive device that derives its destructive force from nuclear reactions, either nuclear fission (fission or atomic bomb) or a combination of fission and nuclear fusion reactions (thermonuclear weapon), producing a nuclear explosion.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Both bomb types release large quantities of energy from relatively small amounts of matter.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nine sovereign states are believed to possess nuclear weapons as of 2026: the United States, Russia, the United Kingdom, France, China, India, Pakistan, North Korea and Israel.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The majority of nuclear weapons have energy yields between 100 and 1,000 kilotons of TNT.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Yields in the low kilotons can destroy cities.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The effects of nuclear weapons include extreme blast damage, heat, ionizing radiation, and firestorms, followed by radioactive nuclear fallout, an electromagnetic pulse, radar blackout, and acute or chronic radiation syndrome in humans and animals.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Hundreds of nuclear explosions would likely cause nuclear winter and nuclear famine.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The first nuclear weapons were developed by the United States in collaboration with the United Kingdom and Canada during World War II in the Manhattan Project.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Production requires a large scientific-industrial complex, primarily for fissile material, either nuclear reactors and reprocessing plants producing plutonium, or uranium enrichment facilities.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear weapons have been used twice in war, in the 1945 atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki that killed between 150,000 and 246,000 people.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear deterrence, including mutually assured destruction, aims to prevent nuclear warfare via the threat of unacceptable damage and the danger of escalation to nuclear holocaust.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A nuclear arms race for weapons and their delivery systems was a defining component of the Cold War.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear weapons have had yields between 50 megatons for the Tsar Bomba, and 10 tons for the W54.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Strategic nuclear weapons are targeted against civilian, industrial, and military infrastructure, while tactical nuclear weapons are intended for battlefield use.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Strategic weapons led to the development of dedicated intercontinental ballistic missiles, submarine-launched ballistic missile, and nuclear strategic bombers, collectively known as the nuclear triad.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Tactical weapons options included shorter-range ground-, air-, and sea-launched missiles, artillery, demolition munitions, torpedoes, and depth charges, but they have become less salient since the end of the Cold War.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Two nuclear-armed states have nuclear sharing arrangements, stationing their weapons in six other countries: US weapons are deployed in Belgium, Germany, Italy, Netherlands, and Turkey; Russian weapons are deployed in Belarus.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Roughly 40 countries have defense policies based on nuclear deterrence, including more than 30 non-nuclear-weapon states under extended deterrence or nuclear umbrella agreements such as the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear weapons are weapons of mass destruction, and their control is a focus of international security through measures to prevent nuclear proliferation, arms control, or nuclear disarmament.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The total global stockpile peaked at more than 64,000 weapons in 1986, and is around 9,600 as of 2025.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Key international agreements and organizations include the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons, the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty and Organization, the International Atomic Energy Agency, nuclear-weapon-free zones, and the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear weapons have only twice been used in warfare, both times by the United States against Japan at the end of World War II.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] These bombings caused injuries that resulted in the deaths of approximately 200,000 civilians and military personnel.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The ethics of these bombings and their role in Japan's surrender are to this day, still subjects of debate.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Since the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, nuclear weapons have been detonated more than 2,000 times for testing and demonstration.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Only a few nations possess such weapons or are suspected of seeking them.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The only countries known to have detonated nuclear weapons—and acknowledge possessing them—are (chronologically by date of first test) the United States, the Soviet Union (succeeded as a nuclear power by Russia), the United Kingdom, France, China, India, Pakistan and North Korea.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Israel is believed to possess nuclear weapons, though, in a policy of deliberate ambiguity, it does not acknowledge having them.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Germany, Italy, Turkey, Netherlands, Belgium, and Belarus are nuclear weapons sharing states.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] South Africa is the only country to have independently developed and then renounced and dismantled its nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] On the 30 October 2025, US President Donald Trump called for renewed nuclear weapons testing in order to keep pace with other nuclear armed states such as Russia and China, but did not make clear whether he referred to nuclear explosive testing or testing of delivery systems for nuclear warheads.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] There are two basic types of nuclear weapons: those that derive the majority of their energy from nuclear fission reactions alone, and those that use fission reactions to begin nuclear fusion reactions that produce a large amount of the total energy output.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] All existing nuclear weapons derive some of their explosive energy from nuclear fission reactions.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Weapons whose explosive output is exclusively from fission reactions are commonly referred to as **atomic bombs** or **atom bombs** (abbreviated as **A-bombs**).
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This has long been noted as something of a misnomer, as their energy comes from the nucleus of the atom, just as it does with fusion weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The latter approach, the "implosion" method, is more sophisticated and more efficient (smaller, less massive, and requiring less of the expensive fissile fuel) than the former.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A major challenge in all nuclear weapon designs is to ensure that a significant fraction of the fuel is consumed before the weapon destroys itself.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The amount of energy released by fission bombs can range from the equivalent of just under a ton to upwards of 500,000 tons (500 kilotons) of TNT (4.2 to 2.1×106 GJ).
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] All fission reactions generate fission products, the remains of the split atomic nuclei.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Many fission products are either highly radioactive (but short-lived) or moderately radioactive (but long-lived), and as such, they are a serious form of radioactive contamination.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Fission products are the principal radioactive component of nuclear fallout.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Another source of radioactivity is the burst of free neutrons produced by the weapon.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] When they collide with other nuclei in the surrounding material, the neutrons transmute those nuclei into other isotopes, altering their stability and making them radioactive.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The most commonly used fissile materials for nuclear weapons applications have been uranium-235 and plutonium-239.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Less commonly used has been uranium-233.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Neptunium-237 and some isotopes of americium may be usable for nuclear explosives as well, but it is not clear that this has ever been implemented, and their plausible use in nuclear weapons is a matter of dispute.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The other basic type of nuclear weapon produces a large proportion of its energy in nuclear fusion reactions.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Such fusion weapons are generally referred to as **thermonuclear weapons** or more colloquially as **hydrogen bombs** (abbreviated as **H-bombs**), as they rely on fusion reactions between isotopes of hydrogen (deuterium and tritium).
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] All such weapons derive a significant portion of their energy from fission reactions used to "trigger" fusion reactions, and fusion reactions can themselves trigger additional fission reactions.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Only six countries—the United States, Russia, the United Kingdom, China, France, and India—have conducted thermonuclear weapon tests.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Whether India has detonated a "true" multi-staged thermonuclear weapon is controversial.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] North Korea claims to have tested a fusion weapon as of January 2016, though this claim is disputed.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Thermonuclear weapons are considered much more difficult to successfully design and execute than primitive fission weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Almost all deployed nuclear weapons use the thermonuclear design because it results in an explosion hundreds of times stronger than that of a fission bomb of similar weight.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Thermonuclear bombs use the energy of a fission bomb to compress and heat fusion fuel.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In the Teller-Ulam design, which accounts for all multi-megaton yield hydrogen bombs, this is accomplished by placing a fission bomb and fusion fuel (tritium, deuterium, or lithium deuteride) in proximity within a special, radiation-reflecting container.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] When the fission bomb is detonated, gamma rays and X-rays emitted first compress the fusion fuel, then heat it to thermonuclear temperatures.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The ensuing fusion reaction creates enormous numbers of high-speed neutrons, which can then induce fission in materials not normally prone to it, such as depleted uranium.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Each of these components is known as a "stage", with the fission bomb as the "primary" and the fusion capsule as the "secondary".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In large, megaton-range hydrogen bombs, about half of the yield comes from the final fissioning of depleted uranium.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Virtually all deployed thermonuclear weapons use this "two-stage" design, but it is possible to add additional fusion stages—each stage igniting a larger amount of fusion fuel in the next stage.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This technique can be used to construct thermonuclear weapons of arbitrarily large yield.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This is in contrast to fission bombs, which are limited in their explosive power due to criticality danger (premature nuclear chain reaction caused by too-large amounts of pre-assembled fissile fuel).
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The largest nuclear weapon ever detonated, the Tsar Bomba of the USSR, which released an energy equivalent of more than 50 megatons of TNT (210 PJ), was a three-stage weapon.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Most thermonuclear weapons are considerably smaller than this, due to practical constraints from missile warhead space and weight requirements.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In the early 1950s the Livermore Laboratory in the United States had plans for the testing of two massive bombs, Gnomon and Sundial, 1 gigaton of TNT and 10 gigatons of TNT respectively.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] There are other types of nuclear weapons as well.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] For example, a boosted fission weapon is a fission bomb that increases its explosive yield through a small number of fusion reactions, but it is not a fusion bomb.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In the boosted bomb, the neutrons produced by the fusion reactions serve primarily to increase the efficiency of the fission bomb.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] There are two types of boosted fission bomb: internally boosted, in which a deuterium-tritium mixture is injected into the bomb core, and externally boosted, in which concentric shells of lithium-deuteride and depleted uranium are layered on the outside of the fission bomb core.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The external method of boosting enabled the USSR to field the first partially thermonuclear weapons, but it is considered obsolete because it demands a spherical bomb geometry, which was adequate during the 1950s arms race when bomber aircraft were the only available delivery vehicles.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The detonation of any nuclear weapon is accompanied by a blast of neutron radiation.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Surrounding a nuclear weapon with suitable materials (such as cobalt or gold) creates a weapon known as a salted bomb.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This device can produce exceptionally large quantities of long-lived radioactive contamination.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] It has been conjectured that such a device could serve as a "doomsday weapon" because such a large quantity of radioactivities with half-lives of decades, lifted into the stratosphere where winds would distribute it around the globe, would make all life on the planet extinct.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In connection with the Strategic Defense Initiative, research into the nuclear pumped laser was conducted under the DOD program Project Excalibur but this did not result in a working weapon.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The concept involves the tapping of the energy of an exploding nuclear bomb to power a single-shot laser that is directed at a distant target.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] During the Starfish Prime high-altitude nuclear test in 1962, an unexpected effect was produced which is called a nuclear electromagnetic pulse.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This is an intense flash of electromagnetic energy produced by a rain of high-energy electrons which in turn are produced by a nuclear bomb's gamma rays.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This flash of energy can permanently destroy or disrupt electronic equipment if insufficiently shielded.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] It has been proposed to use this effect to disable an enemy's military and civilian infrastructure as an adjunct to other nuclear or conventional military operations.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] By itself it could as well be useful to terrorists for crippling a nation's economic electronics-based infrastructure.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Because the effect is most effectively produced by high altitude nuclear detonations (by military weapons delivered by air, though ground bursts also produce EMP effects over a localized area), it can produce damage to electronics over a wide, even continental, geographical area.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Research has been done into the possibility of pure fusion bombs: nuclear weapons that consist of fusion reactions without requiring a fission bomb to initiate them.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Such a device might provide a simpler path to thermonuclear weapons than one that required the development of fission weapons first, and pure fusion weapons would create significantly less nuclear fallout than other thermonuclear weapons because they would not disperse fission products.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear isomers provide a possible pathway to fissionless fusion bombs.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] These are naturally occurring isotopes (178m2Hf being a prominent example) which exist in an elevated energy state.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Mechanisms to release this energy as bursts of gamma radiation (as in the hafnium controversy) have been proposed as possible triggers for conventional thermonuclear reactions.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Antimatter, which consists of particles resembling ordinary matter particles in most of their properties but having opposite electric charge, has been considered as a trigger mechanism for nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A major obstacle is the difficulty of producing antimatter in large enough quantities, and there is no evidence that it is feasible beyond the military domain.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] However, the US Air Force funded studies of the physics of antimatter in the Cold War, and began considering its possible use in weapons, not just as a trigger, but as the explosive itself.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A fourth generation nuclear weapon design is related to, and relies upon, the same principle as antimatter-catalyzed nuclear pulse propulsion.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Most variation in nuclear weapon design is for the purpose of achieving different yields for different situations, and in manipulating design elements to attempt to minimize weapon size, radiation hardness or requirements for special materials, especially fissile fuel or tritium.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Some nuclear weapons are designed for special purposes; most of these are for non-strategic (decisively war-winning) purposes and are referred to as tactical nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The neutron bomb purportedly conceived by Sam Cohen is a thermonuclear weapon that yields a relatively small explosion but a relatively large amount of neutron radiation.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Such a weapon could, according to tacticians, be used to cause massive biological casualties while leaving inanimate infrastructure mostly intact and creating minimal fallout.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Because high energy neutrons are capable of penetrating dense matter, such as tank armor, neutron warheads were procured in the 1980s (though not deployed in Europe) for use as tactical payloads for US Army artillery shells (200 mm W79 and 155 mm W82) and short range missile forces.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Soviet authorities announced similar intentions for neutron warhead deployment in Europe; indeed, they claimed to have originally invented the neutron bomb, but their deployment on USSR tactical nuclear forces is unverifiable.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A type of nuclear explosive most suitable for use by ground special forces was the Special Atomic Demolition Munition, or SADM, sometimes popularly known as a suitcase nuke.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] These weapons require plutonium fuel and are particularly "dirty".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] They also demand especially stringent security precautions in their storage and deployment.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Small "tactical" nuclear weapons were deployed for use as antiaircraft weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Examples include the USAF AIR-2 Genie, the AIM-26 Falcon and US Army Nike Hercules.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Missile interceptors such as the Sprint and the Spartan also used small nuclear warheads (optimized to produce neutron or X-ray flux) but were for use against enemy strategic warheads.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Other small, or tactical, nuclear weapons were deployed by naval forces for use primarily as antisubmarine weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] These included nuclear depth bombs or nuclear armed torpedoes.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear mines for use on land or at sea are also possibilities.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The system used to deliver a nuclear weapon to its target is an important factor affecting both nuclear weapon design and nuclear strategy.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The design, development, and maintenance of delivery systems are among the most expensive parts of a nuclear weapons program; they account, for example, for 57% of the financial resources spent by the United States on nuclear weapons projects since 1940.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The simplest method for delivering a nuclear weapon is a gravity bomb dropped from aircraft; this was the method used by the United States against Japan in 1945.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This method places few restrictions on the size of the weapon.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] It does, however, limit attack range, response time to an impending attack, and the number of weapons that a country can field at the same time.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] With miniaturization, nuclear bombs can be delivered by both strategic bombers and tactical fighter-bombers.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This method is the primary means of nuclear weapons delivery; the majority of US nuclear warheads, for example, are free-fall gravity bombs, namely the B61, which is being improved upon to this day.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Preferable from a strategic point of view is a nuclear weapon mounted on a missile, which can use a ballistic trajectory to deliver the warhead over the horizon.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] More advanced systems, such as multiple independently targetable reentry vehicles (MIRVs), can launch multiple warheads at different targets from one missile, reducing the chance of a successful missile defense.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Today, missiles are most common among systems designed for delivery of nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Making a warhead small enough to fit onto a missile, though, can be difficult.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Tactical weapons have involved the most variety of delivery types, including not only gravity bombs and missiles but also artillery shells, land mines, and nuclear depth charges and torpedoes for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] An atomic mortar has been tested by the United States.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Small, two-man portable tactical weapons (somewhat misleadingly referred to as suitcase bombs), such as the Special Atomic Demolition Munition, have been developed, although the difficulty of combining sufficient yield with portability limits their military utility.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear warfare strategy is a set of policies that deal with preventing or fighting a nuclear war.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The policy of trying to prevent an attack by a nuclear weapon from another country by threatening nuclear retaliation is known as the strategy of nuclear deterrence.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The goal in deterrence is to always maintain a second strike capability (the ability of a country to respond to a nuclear attack with one of its own) and potentially to strive for first strike status (the ability to destroy an enemy's nuclear forces before they could retaliate).
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] During the Cold War, policy and military theorists considered the sorts of policies that might prevent a nuclear attack, and they developed game theory models that could lead to stable deterrence conditions.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Different forms of nuclear weapons delivery (see above) allow for different types of nuclear strategies.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The goals of any strategy are generally to make it difficult for an enemy to launch a pre-emptive strike against the weapon system and difficult to defend against the delivery of the weapon during a potential conflict.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This can mean keeping weapon locations hidden, such as deploying them on submarines or land mobile transporter erector launchers whose locations are difficult to track, or it can mean protecting weapons by burying them in hardened missile silo bunkers.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Other components of nuclear strategies included using missile defenses to destroy the missiles before they land or implementing civil defense measures using early-warning systems to evacuate citizens to safe areas before an attack.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Critics of nuclear war strategy often suggest that a nuclear war between two nations would result in mutual annihilation.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] From this point of view, the significance of nuclear weapons is to deter war because any nuclear war would escalate out of mutual distrust and fear, resulting in mutually assured destruction.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This threat of national, if not global, destruction has been a strong motivation for anti-nuclear weapons activism.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Critics from the peace movement and within the military establishment have questioned the usefulness of such weapons in the current military climate.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Another deterrence position is that nuclear proliferation can be desirable.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In this case, it is argued that, unlike conventional weapons, nuclear weapons deter all-out war between states, and they succeeded in doing this during the Cold War between the US and the Soviet Union.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Some prominent neo-realist scholars, such as Kenneth Waltz and John Mearsheimer, have argued, along the lines of Gallois, that some forms of nuclear proliferation would decrease the likelihood of total war, especially in troubled regions of the world where there exists a single nuclear-weapon state.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Aside from the public opinion that opposes proliferation in any form, there are two schools of thought on the matter: those, like Mearsheimer, who favored selective proliferation, and Waltz, who was somewhat more non-interventionist.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Interest in proliferation and the stability-instability paradox that it generates continues to this day, with ongoing debate about indigenous Japanese and South Korean nuclear deterrent against North Korea.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The threat of potentially suicidal terrorists possessing nuclear weapons (a form of nuclear terrorism) complicates the decision process.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The prospect of mutually assured destruction might not deter an enemy who expects to die in the confrontation.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Further, if the initial act is from a stateless terrorist instead of a sovereign nation, there might not be a nation or specific target to retaliate against.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] It has been argued, especially after the September 11, 2001, attacks, that this complication calls for a new nuclear strategy, one that is distinct from that which gave relative stability during the Cold War.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Since 1996, the United States has had a policy of allowing the targeting of its nuclear weapons at terrorists armed with weapons of mass destruction.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Graham Allison makes a similar case, arguing that the key to expanded deterrence is coming up with ways of tracing nuclear material to the country that forged the fissile material.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] "After a nuclear bomb detonates, nuclear forensics cops would collect debris samples and send them to a laboratory for radiological analysis.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] By identifying unique attributes of the fissile material, including its impurities and contaminants, one could trace the path back to its origin." The process is analogous to identifying a criminal by fingerprints.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Because they are weapons of mass destruction, the proliferation and possible use of nuclear weapons are important issues in international relations and diplomacy.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In most countries, the use of nuclear force can only be authorized by the head of government or head of state.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Despite controls and regulations governing nuclear weapons, there is an inherent danger of "accidents, mistakes, false alarms, blackmail, theft, and sabotage".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In the late 1940s, lack of mutual trust prevented the United States and the Soviet Union from making progress on arms control agreements.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The Russell–Einstein Manifesto was issued in London on 9 July 1955, by Bertrand Russell in the midst of the Cold War.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] It highlighted the dangers posed by nuclear weapons and called for world leaders to seek peaceful resolutions to international conflict.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The signatories included eleven preeminent intellectuals and scientists, including Albert Einstein, who signed it just days before his death on 18 April 1955.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A few days after the release, philanthropist Cyrus S.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Eaton offered to sponsor a conference—called for in the manifesto—in Pugwash, Nova Scotia, Eaton's birthplace.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This conference was to be the first of the Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs, held in July 1957.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] By the 1960s, steps were taken to limit both the proliferation of nuclear weapons to other countries and the environmental effects of nuclear testing.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In 1957, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) was established under the mandate of the United Nations to encourage development of peaceful applications of nuclear technology, provide international safeguards against its misuse, and facilitate the application of safety measures in its use.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In 1996, many nations signed the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty, which prohibits all testing of nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A testing ban imposes a significant hindrance to nuclear arms development by any complying country.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The treaty requires the ratification by 44 specific states before it can go into force; as of 2012, the ratification of eight of these states is still required.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Additional treaties and agreements have governed nuclear weapons stockpiles between the countries with the two largest stockpiles, the United States and the Soviet Union, and later between the United States and Russia.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] These include treaties such as SALT II (never ratified), START I (expired), INF, START II (never in effect), SORT, and New START, as well as non-binding agreements such as SALT I and the Presidential Nuclear Initiatives of 1991.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Even when they did not enter into force, these agreements helped limit and later reduce the numbers and types of nuclear weapons between the United States and the Soviet Union/Russia.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear weapons have also been opposed by agreements between countries.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Many nations have been declared Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zones, areas where nuclear weapons production and deployment are prohibited, through the use of treaties.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The Treaty of Tlatelolco (1967) prohibited any production or deployment of nuclear weapons in Latin America and the Caribbean, and the Treaty of Pelindaba (1964) prohibits nuclear weapons in many African countries.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] As recently as 2006 a Central Asian Nuclear Weapon Free Zone was established among the former Soviet republics of Central Asia prohibiting nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In 1996, the International Court of Justice, the highest court of the United Nations, issued an Advisory Opinion concerned with the "Legality of the Threat or Use of Nuclear Weapons".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The court ruled that the use or threat of use of nuclear weapons would violate various articles of international law, including the Geneva Conventions, the Hague Conventions, the UN Charter, and the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Given the unique, destructive characteristics of nuclear weapons, the International Committee of the Red Cross calls on States to ensure that these weapons are never used, irrespective of whether they consider them lawful or not.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Additionally, there have been other, specific actions meant to discourage countries from developing nuclear arms.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In the wake of the tests by India and Pakistan in 1998, economic sanctions were (temporarily) levied against both countries, though neither were signatories with the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] One of the stated *casus belli* for the initiation of the 2003 Iraq War was an accusation by the United States that Iraq was actively pursuing nuclear arms (though this was soon discovered not to be the case as the program had been discontinued).
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In 1981, Israel had bombed a nuclear reactor being constructed in Osirak, Iraq, in what it called an attempt to halt Iraq's previous nuclear arms ambitions; in 2007, Israel bombed another reactor being constructed in Syria.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In 2013, Mark Diesendorf said that governments of France, India, North Korea, Pakistan, UK, and South Africa have used nuclear power or research reactors to assist nuclear weapons development or to contribute to their supplies of nuclear explosives from military reactors.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In 2017, 122 countries mainly in the Global South voted in favor of adopting the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons, which eventually entered into force in 2021.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The Doomsday Clock measures the likelihood of a human-made global catastrophe and is published annually by the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The Doomsday Clock is set a certain time from midnight, midnight being the time of global catastrophe.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In 2023, following the escalation of nuclear threats during the Russo-Ukrainian war, the doomsday clock was set to 90 seconds, the highest likelihood of global catastrophe since the existence of the Doomsday Clock.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Given the lack of progress towards peace in Ukraine, the Doomsday Clock was moved to 89 seconds to midnight in 2025.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] As of 2024, Russia has intensified nuclear threats in Ukraine and is reportedly planning to place nuclear weapons in orbit, breaching the 1967 Outer Space Treaty.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] China is significantly expanding its nuclear arsenal, with projections of more than 1,000 warheads by 2030 and up to 1,500 by 2035.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] North Korea is progressing in intercontinental ballistic missile tests and has a mutual-defense treaty with Russia, exchanging artillery for possible missile technology.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Iran is currently viewed as a nuclear "threshold" state.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Nuclear disarmament refers to both the act of reducing or eliminating nuclear weapons and to the end state of a nuclear-free world, in which nuclear weapons are eliminated.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Beginning with the 1963 Partial Test Ban Treaty and continuing through the 1996 Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty, there have been many treaties to limit or reduce nuclear weapons testing and stockpiles.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The 1968 Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty has as one of its explicit conditions that all signatories must "pursue negotiations in good faith" towards the long-term goal of "complete disarmament".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The nuclear-weapon states have largely treated that aspect of the agreement as "decorative" and without force.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Only one country—South Africa—has ever fully renounced nuclear weapons they had independently developed.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The former Soviet republics of Belarus, Kazakhstan, and Ukraine returned Soviet nuclear arms stationed in their countries to Russia after the collapse of the USSR.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Proponents of nuclear disarmament say that it would lessen the probability of nuclear war, especially accidentally.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Critics of nuclear disarmament say that it would undermine the present nuclear peace and deterrence and would lead to increased global instability.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Various American elder statesmen, who were in office during the Cold War period, have been advocating the elimination of nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] These officials include Henry Kissinger, George Shultz, Sam Nunn and William Perry.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Krauss stated that "no issue carries more importance to the long-term health and security of humanity than the effort to reduce, and perhaps one day, rid the world of nuclear weapons".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In January 1986, Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev publicly proposed a three-stage program for abolishing the world's nuclear weapons by the end of the 20th century.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A CNN poll from April 2010 indicated that the American public was nearly evenly split on the issue.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Some analysts have argued that nuclear weapons have made the world relatively safer, with peace through deterrence and through the stability–instability paradox, including in south Asia.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Kenneth Waltz has argued that nuclear weapons have helped keep an uneasy peace, and further nuclear weapon proliferation might even help avoid the large scale conventional wars that were so common before their invention at the end of World War II.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] But former Secretary Henry Kissinger said in 2010 that there is a new danger, which cannot be addressed by deterrence: "The classical notion of deterrence was that there was some consequences before which aggressors and evildoers would recoil.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] In a world of suicide bombers, that calculation doesn't operate in any comparable way".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] George Shultz has said, "If you think of the people who are doing suicide attacks, and people like that get a nuclear weapon, they are almost by definition not deterrable".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] As of early 2019, more than 90% of world's 13,865 nuclear weapons were owned by Russia and the United States.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] The UN Office for Disarmament Affairs (UNODA) is a department of the United Nations Secretariat established in January 1998 as part of the United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan's plan to reform the UN as presented in his report to the General Assembly in July 1997.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Its goal is to promote nuclear disarmament and non-proliferation and the strengthening of the disarmament regimes in respect to other weapons of mass destruction, chemical and biological weapons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] It also promotes disarmament efforts in the area of conventional weapons, especially land mines and small arms, which are often the weapons of choice in contemporary conflicts.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Comparative studies have shown that nuclear weapons programs produce systems of secrecy, reduction in democratic practices, and concentration of power in the executive branch.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] These have had different specific expressions in different countries, ranging from systems with some ostensible transparency and accountability, to systems where there is essentially no public participation in nuclear decision-making, even in some democracies.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] Different nuclear-armed states, over time, developed different approaches to the question of nuclear weapons use decisions are made, and by whom they can be made.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] This is referred to as "launch authority." As many of these procedures are treated as deeply secret, the exact details are often debated.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] A general historical trend, however, is that new nuclear states have often taken many years to formalize their procedures for authorizing nuclear weapons use, and that there are often an early reliance on military control of the weapons, with differing degrees of centralized civilian control.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p01] At times, states have relied to greater or lesser extents on automation, computerization, and increasingly complex command, control, and communications systems to facilitate the use of nuclear weapons and the detection of potential use against them.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Even before the first nuclear weapons had been developed, scientists involved with the Manhattan Project were divided over the use of the weapon.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The role of the two atomic bombings of the country in Japan's surrender and the US's ethical justification for them has been the subject of scholarly and popular debate for decades.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The question of whether nations should have nuclear weapons, or test them, has been continually and nearly universally controversial.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The production and deployment of nuclear weapons has involved many accidents that resulted in either some radiation casualties, or the near-miss possibility of the unauthorized and unintended detonation of a nuclear weapon.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Governmental nuclear agencies frequently point to their procedures and technical safeguards as what has prevented accidental nuclear explosions.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Over 500 atmospheric nuclear weapons tests were conducted at various sites around the world from 1945 to 1980.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Radioactive fallout from nuclear weapons testing was first drawn to public attention in 1954 when the Castle Bravo hydrogen bomb test at the Pacific Proving Grounds contaminated the crew and catch of the Japanese fishing boat *Lucky Dragon*.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] One of the fishermen died in Japan seven months later, and the fear of contaminated tuna led to a temporary boycotting of the popular staple in Japan.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The incident caused widespread concern around the world, especially regarding the effects of nuclear fallout and atmospheric nuclear testing, and "provided a decisive impetus for the emergence of the anti-nuclear weapons movement in many countries".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] As public awareness and concern mounted over the possible health hazards associated with exposure to the nuclear fallout, various studies were done to assess the extent of the hazard.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] As of March 2009, the US is the only nation that compensates nuclear test victims.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Since the Radiation Exposure Compensation Act of 1990, more than $1.38 billion in compensation has been approved.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The money is going to people who took part in the tests, notably at the Nevada Test Site, and to others exposed to the radiation.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In addition, leakage of byproducts of nuclear weapon production into groundwater has been an ongoing issue, particularly at the Hanford site.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Some scientists estimate that a nuclear war with 100 Hiroshima-size nuclear explosions on cities could cost the lives of tens of millions of people from long-term climatic effects alone.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The climatology hypothesis is that *if* each city firestorms, a great deal of soot could be thrown up into the atmosphere which could blanket the earth, cutting out sunlight for years on end, causing the disruption of food chains, in what is termed a nuclear winter.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] People near the Hiroshima explosion and who managed to survive the explosion subsequently suffered a variety of horrible medical effects.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] With those who do shelter in place, and or evacuate, experiencing a total dose that would be negligible in comparison to someone who just went about their life as normal.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] For example, staying indoors until after the most hazardous fallout isotope, I-131 decays away to 0.1% of its initial quantity after ten half-lives—roughly 80 days for I-131, could avoid most of the risk of contracting thyroid cancer.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Nuclear war could yield unprecedented human death tolls and habitat destruction.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Detonating large numbers of nuclear weapons would have an immediate, short term and long-term effects on the climate, potentially causing cold weather known as a "nuclear winter".
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In 1982, Brian Martin estimated that a US–Soviet nuclear exchange might kill 400–450 million directly, mostly in the United States, Europe and Russia, and maybe several hundred million more through follow-up consequences in those same areas.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Many scholars have posited that a global thermonuclear war with Cold War-era stockpiles, or even with the current smaller stockpiles, may lead to the extinction of the human race.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The *International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War* believe that nuclear war could indirectly contribute to human extinction via secondary effects, including environmental consequences, societal breakdown, and economic collapse.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] It has been estimated that a relatively small-scale nuclear exchange between India and Pakistan involving 100 Hiroshima yield (15 kilotons) weapons, could cause a nuclear winter and kill more than a billion people.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] According to a peer-reviewed study published in the journal *Nature Food* in August 2022, a full-scale nuclear war between the US and Russia would directly kill 360 million people and more than 5 billion people would die from starvation.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] More than 2 billion people could die from a smaller-scale nuclear war between India and Pakistan.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The Aldermaston marches continued into the late 1960s when tens of thousands of people took part in the four-day marches.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In 1959, a letter in the *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists* was the start of a successful campaign to stop the Atomic Energy Commission dumping radioactive waste in the sea 19 kilometers from Boston.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In 1962, Linus Pauling won the Nobel Peace Prize for his work to stop the atmospheric testing of nuclear weapons, and the "Ban the Bomb" movement spread.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In 1963, many countries ratified the Partial Test Ban Treaty prohibiting atmospheric nuclear testing.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Radioactive fallout became less of an issue and the anti-nuclear weapons movement went into decline for some years.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] A resurgence of interest occurred amid European and American fears of nuclear war in the 1980s.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] According to an audit by the Brookings Institution, between 1940 and 1996, the US spent $11.9 trillion in present-day terms on nuclear weapons programs, 57% of which was spent on building nuclear weapons delivery systems.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] 6.3% of the total amount, $749 billion in present-day terms, was spent on environmental remediation and nuclear waste management—for example, cleaning up the Hanford site—and 7% of the total $820 billion was spent on making nuclear weapons themselves.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Peaceful nuclear explosions (PNEs) are nuclear explosions conducted for non-military purposes, such as activities related to economic development including the creation of canals.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] During the 1960s and 1970s, both the United States and the Soviet Union conducted a number of PNEs.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The United States created plans for several uses of PNEs, including Operation Plowshare.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Six of the explosions by the Soviet Union are considered to have been of an applied nature, not just tests.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The United States and the Soviet Union later halted their programs.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Definitions and limits are covered in the Peaceful Nuclear Explosions Treaty of 1976.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The stalled Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty of 1996 would prohibit all nuclear explosions, regardless of whether they are for peaceful purposes or not.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In the first decades of the 19th century, physics was revolutionized with developments in the understanding of the nature of atoms including the discoveries in atomic theory by John Dalton.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Around the turn of the 20th century, it was discovered by Hans Geiger and Ernest Marsden and then Ernest Rutherford, that atoms had a highly dense, very small, charged central core called an atomic nucleus.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In 1898, Pierre and Marie Curie discovered that pitchblende, an ore of uranium, contained a substance—which they named radium—that emitted large amounts of radiation.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Ernest Rutherford and Frederick Soddy identified that atoms were breaking down and turning into different elements.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Hopes were raised among scientists and laymen that the elements around us could contain tremendous amounts of unseen energy, waiting to be harnessed.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In 1905, Albert Einstein described this potential in his famous equation, *E* = *mc*2.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] At the time however, there was no known mechanism which could be used to unlock the vast energy potential that was theorized to exist inside the atom.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The only particle then known to exist within the nucleus was the positively-charged proton, which would act to repel protons set in motion towards it.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Then in 1932, a key breakthrough was made with the discovery of the neutron.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Having no electric charge, the neutron is able to penetrate the nucleus with relative ease.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In January 1933, the Nazis came to power in Germany and suppressed Jewish scientists.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Physicist Leo Szilard fled to London where, in 1934, he patented the idea of a nuclear chain reaction using neutrons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The patent also introduced the term *critical mass* to describe the minimum amount of material required to sustain the chain reaction and its potential to cause an explosion (British patent 630,726).
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The patent was not about an atomic bomb *per se*, as the possibility of chain reaction was still very speculative.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Szilard subsequently assigned the patent to the British Admiralty so that it could be covered by the Official Secrets Act.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] This work of Szilard's was ahead of the time, five years before the public discovery of nuclear fission and eight years before a working nuclear reactor.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] When he coined the term *neutron inducted chain reaction*, he was not sure about the use of isotopes or standard forms of elements.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Despite this uncertainty, he correctly theorized uranium and thorium as primary candidates for such a reaction, along with beryllium which was later determined to be unnecessary in practice.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Szilard joined Enrico Fermi in developing the first uranium-fuelled nuclear reactor, Chicago Pile-1, which was activated at the University of Chicago in 1942.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In Paris in 1934, Irène and Frédéric Joliot-Curie discovered that artificial radioactivity could be induced in stable elements by bombarding them with alpha particles; in Italy Enrico Fermi reported similar results when bombarding uranium with neutrons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] He mistakenly believed he had discovered elements 93 and 94, naming them ausenium and hesperium.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In 1938 it was realized these were in fact fission products.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In December 1938, Otto Hahn and Fritz Strassmann reported that they had detected the element barium after bombarding uranium with neutrons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Lise Meitner and Otto Robert Frisch correctly interpreted these results as being due to the splitting of the uranium atom.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Frisch confirmed this experimentally on January 13, 1939.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] They gave the process the name "fission" because of its similarity to the splitting of a cell into two new cells.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Even before it was published, news of Meitner's and Frisch's interpretation crossed the Atlantic.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In their second publication on nuclear fission in February 1939, Hahn and Strassmann predicted the existence and liberation of additional neutrons during the fission process, opening up the possibility of a nuclear chain reaction.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] This patent was applied for on May 4, 1939, but only granted in 1950, being withheld by French authorities in the meantime.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Uranium appears in nature primarily in two isotopes: uranium-238 and uranium-235.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] When the nucleus of uranium-235 absorbs a neutron, it undergoes nuclear fission, releasing energy and, on average, 2.5 neutrons.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Because uranium-235 releases more neutrons than it absorbs, it can support a chain reaction and so is described as fissile.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Uranium-238, on the other hand, is not fissile as it does not normally undergo fission when it absorbs a neutron.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] By the start of the war in September 1939, many scientists likely to be persecuted by the Nazis had already escaped.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Physicists on both sides were well aware of the possibility of utilizing nuclear fission as a weapon, but no one was quite sure how it could be engineered.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In August 1939, concerned that Germany might have its own project to develop fission-based weapons, Albert Einstein signed a letter to U.S.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Roosevelt responded by setting up the Uranium Committee under Lyman James Briggs but, with little initial funding ($6,000), progress was slow.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] It was not until the U.S. entered the war in December 1941 that Washington decided to commit the necessary resources to a top-secret high priority bomb project.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] Organized research first began in Britain as part of the Tube Alloys project, the world's first nuclear weapons project, which also involved Canada.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The Maud Committee was set up following the work of Frisch and Rudolf Peierls who calculated uranium-235's critical mass and found it to be much smaller than previously thought which meant that a deliverable bomb should be possible.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] In the February 1940 Frisch–Peierls memorandum they stated that: "The energy liberated in the explosion of such a super-bomb...will, for an instant, produce a temperature comparable to that of the interior of the sun.
[src:big-science/atomic-bomb-p02] The blast from such an explosion would destroy life in a wide area.
[src:big-science/big-science] While science and technology have always been important to and driven by warfare, the increase in military funding of science following the second World War was on a scale wholly unprecedented.
[src:big-science/big-science] The bulk of these last two activities took place in a new form of research facility: the government-sponsored laboratory, employing thousands of technicians and scientists, managed by universities (in this case, the University of California and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology).
[src:big-science/big-science] The need of a strong scientific research establishment was obvious in the shadow of the first atomic weapons to any country seeking to play a prominent role in world affairs.
[src:big-science/big-science] After the success of the Manhattan Project, governments became the chief patron of science, and the character of the scientific establishment underwent several key changes.
[src:big-science/big-science] This was especially marked in the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War, but also to a lesser extent in many other countries.
[src:big-science/big-science] Towards the end of the 20th century, not only projects in basic physics and astronomy, but also in life sciences became big sciences, such as the massive Human Genome Project.
[src:big-science/big-science] The heavy investment of government and industrial interests into academic science has also blurred the line between public and private research, where entire academic departments, even at public universities, are often financed by private companies.
[src:big-science/big-science] Not all Big Science is related to the military concerns which were at its origins.
[src:big-science/big-science] The era of Big Science has provoked criticism that it undermines the basic principles of the scientific method.
[src:big-science/big-science] Increased government funding has often meant increased military funding, which some claim subverts the Enlightenment-era ideal of science as a pure quest for knowledge.
[src:big-science/big-science] For example, historian Paul Forman has argued that during World War II and the Cold War, the massive scale of defense-related funding prompted a shift in physics from basic to applied research.
[src:big-science/big-science] In addition, widespread sharing of scientific knowledge is necessary for rapid progress for both basic and applied sciences.
[src:big-science/big-science] However the sharing of data can be impeded for a number of reasons.
[src:big-science/big-science] For example, scientific findings can be classified by military interests or patented by corporate ones.
[src:big-science/big-science] Grant competitions, while they stimulate interest in a topic, can also increase secretiveness among scientists because application evaluators may value uniqueness more than incremental, collaborative inquiry.
[src:big-science/big-science] The popularization of the term "Big Science" is usually attributed to an article by Alvin M.
[src:big-science/big-science] Weinberg, then director of Oak Ridge National Laboratory, published in *Science* in 1961.
[src:big-science/big-science] Eisenhower's farewell address, in which the departing U.S. president warned against the dangers of what he called the "military–industrial complex" and the potential "domination of the nation's scholars by Federal employment, project allocations, and the power of money".
[src:big-science/big-science] Since Weinberg's article there have been many historical and sociological studies on the effects of Big Science both in and out of the laboratory.
[src:big-science/big-science] Soon after that article, Derek J. de Solla Price gave a series of lectures that were published in 1963 as *Little Science, Big Science*.
[src:big-science/big-science] The book describes the historical and sociological transition from "small science" to "big science" and the qualitative differences between the two; it inspired the field of scientometrics as well as new perspectives on large-scale science in other fields.
[src:big-science/big-science] The Harvard historian Peter Galison has written several books addressing the formation of big science.
[src:big-science/big-science] Major themes include the evolution of experimental design, from table-top experiments to today's large-scale collider projects; accompanying changes in standards of evidence; and discourse patterns across researchers whose expertise only partially overlaps.
[src:big-science/big-science] Galison introduced the notion of "trading zones," borrowed from the sociolinguistic study of pidgins, to characterize how such groups learn to interact.
[src:big-science/buzzword] A **buzzword** is a word or phrase, new or already existing, that becomes popular for a period of time.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Buzzwords often derive from technical terms yet often have much of the original technical meaning removed through fashionable use, being simply used to impress others.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Some buzzwords retain their true technical meaning when used in the correct contexts; for example, artificial intelligence or big data.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Buzzwords often originate in jargon, acronyms, or neologisms.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Examples of overworked business buzzwords include *synergy*, *vertical*, *dynamic*, *cyber* and *strategy*.
[src:big-science/buzzword] It has been stated that businesses could not operate without buzzwords, as they are the shorthands or internal shortcuts that make perfect sense to people informed of the context.
[src:big-science/buzzword] However, a useful buzzword can become co-opted into general popular speech and lose its usefulness.
[src:big-science/buzzword] According to management professor Robert Kreitner, "Buzzwords are the literary equivalent of Gresham's law.
[src:big-science/buzzword] They will drive out good ideas." Buzzwords, or buzz-phrases such as "all on the same page", can also be seen in business as a way to make people feel like there is a mutual understanding.
[src:big-science/buzzword] As most workplaces use a specialized jargon, which could be argued is another form of buzzwords, it allows quicker communication.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Indeed, many new hires feel more like "part of the team" the quicker they learn the buzzwords of their new workplace.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Buzzwords permeate people's working lives so much that many do not realize that they are using them.
[src:big-science/buzzword] The vice president of CSC Index, Rich DeVane, notes that buzzwords describe not only a trend, but also what can be considered a "ticket of entry" with regard to being considered as a successful organization – "What people find tiresome is each consulting firm's attempt to put a different spin on it.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Buzzwords also feature prominently in politics, where they can result in a process which "privileges rhetoric over reality, producing policies that are 'operationalized' first and only 'conceptualized' at a later date".
[src:big-science/buzzword] The resulting political speech is known for "eschewing reasoned debate (as characterized by the use of evidence and structured argument), instead employing language exclusively for the purposes of control and manipulation".
[src:big-science/buzzword] The *Concise Oxford English Dictionary* defines a buzzword (hyphenating the term as *buzz-word*) as a slogan, or as a fashionable piece of jargon: a chic, fashionable, voguish, trendy word a la mode.
[src:big-science/buzzword] It has been asserted that buzzwords do not simply appear, they are created by a group of people working within a business as a means to generate hype.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Buzzwords are most closely associated with management and have become the vocabulary that is known as "management speak": Using a pompous or magisterial term, of or relating to a particular subject employed to impress those outside of the field of expertise.
[src:big-science/buzzword] It could also be called buzz phrase or loaded word.
[src:big-science/buzzword] What this means is that when a manager uses a said buzzword, most other people do not hear the meaning, and instead just see it as a buzzword.
[src:big-science/buzzword] However it has been said that buzzwords are almost a "necessary evil" of management, as a way to inspire their team, but also stroke their own egos.
[src:big-science/buzzword] With that being said, a buzzword is not necessarily a bad thing, as many disciplines thrive with the introduction of new terms which can be called buzzwords.
[src:big-science/buzzword] These can also cross over into pop culture and indeed even into everyday life.
[src:big-science/buzzword] With media channels now operating through many media, such as television, radio, print and increasingly digital (especially with the rise of social media), a "buzzword" can catch on and rapidly be adapted through the world.
[src:big-science/buzzword] The origin of buzzwords can be seen in Hallgren & Weiss (1946) as coming from business students studying at Harvard University as a way to help them gain better results from their studies.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Such language terms were collated and then became what is known today as "buzzwords".
[src:big-science/buzzword] During the early years of buzzwords, buzzwords were used by students as a means to enable them to quickly recall items of importance.
[src:big-science/buzzword] As an example, "If his analysis does not highlight the most important problems he has 'poor focus', and if he fails to emphasize important recommendations he will be accused of 'tinkering'.
[src:big-science/buzzword] If the sequence for the 'implementation' of the recommendations is not good it is a matter of 'poor timing'.
[src:big-science/buzzword] To succeed, the student must 'get on top of the problem'.
[src:big-science/buzzword] He must 'hit the problem' and not 'shadow box' it.
[src:big-science/buzzword] If he cannot do these things he might just as well 'turn in his suit'".
[src:big-science/buzzword] Students have used many different buzzwords to describe the situation that they are in, and how this might affect a moment in their everyday life.
[src:big-science/buzzword] From studying these business students, Hallgren & Weiss (1946) noticed that business students could speak with apparent authority.
[src:big-science/buzzword] It also seemed as if using the right buzzword was more important than what the student came up with as an answer.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Buzzwords have a strong influence on business culture and are commonly used in business speak.
[src:big-science/buzzword] LinkedIn publishes an annual list of buzzwords to avoid in creating résumés (British English: CVs) – "trite, empty words that may sound good to your ear but say almost nothing".
[src:big-science/buzzword] The 2014 list: *motivated*, *passionate*, *creative*, *driven*, *extensive experience*, *responsible*, *strategic*, *track record*, *organizational*, and *expert*.
[src:big-science/buzzword] When people are approaching a meeting where they expect the presenters to use many buzzwords, they may prepare a game of buzzword bingo, where players score points each time a particular buzzword is used.
[src:big-science/buzzword] Patch Products has published a board game called *Buzzword*.
[src:big-science/buzzword] The "Weird Al" Yankovic album *Mandatory Fun* contains the song "Mission Statement", which is full of what he describes as the "ridiculous double-speak and meaningless buzzwords" in office environments.
[src:big-science/cern] The **European Organization for Nuclear Research**, known as **CERN** (/sɜːrn/; French pronunciation: [sɛʁn]; *Organisation européenne pour la recherche nucléaire*), is an intergovernmental organization that operates the largest particle physics laboratory in the world.
[src:big-science/cern] Established in 1954, it is based in Meyrin, a western suburb of Geneva, on the France–Switzerland border.
[src:big-science/cern] Israel, admitted in 2013, is the only full member geographically out of Europe.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN is an official United Nations General Assembly observer.
[src:big-science/cern] The acronym CERN is also used to refer to the laboratory; in 2024, it had 2,704 scientific, technical, and administrative staff members, and hosted about 12,406 users from institutions in more than 80 countries.
[src:big-science/cern] In 2016, CERN generated 49 petabytes of data.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN's main function is to provide the particle accelerators and other infrastructure needed for high-energy physics research – consequently, numerous experiments have been constructed at CERN through international collaborations.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN is the site of the Large Hadron Collider (LHC), the world's largest and highest-energy particle collider.
[src:big-science/cern] The main site at Meyrin hosts a large computing facility, which is primarily used to store and analyze data from experiments, as well as simulate events.
[src:big-science/cern] As researchers require remote access to these facilities, the lab has historically been a major wide area network hub.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN is also the birthplace of the World Wide Web.
[src:big-science/cern] The convention establishing CERN was ratified on 29 September 1954 by 12 countries in Western Europe.
[src:big-science/cern] The acronym CERN originally represented the French words for *Conseil Européen pour la Recherche Nucléaire* ('European Council for Nuclear Research'), which was a provisional council for building the laboratory, established by 12 European governments in 1952.
[src:big-science/cern] During these early years, the council worked at the University of Copenhagen under the direction of Niels Bohr before moving to its present site near Geneva.
[src:big-science/cern] The acronym was retained for the new laboratory after the provisional council was dissolved, even though the name changed to the current *Organisation européenne pour la recherche nucléaire* ('European Organization for Nuclear Research') in 1954.
[src:big-science/cern] According to Lew Kowarski, a former director of CERN, when the name was changed, the abbreviation could have become the awkward OERN, and Werner Heisenberg said that this could "still be CERN even if the name is [not]".
[src:big-science/cern] CERN's first president was Sir Benjamin Lockspeiser.
[src:big-science/cern] Edoardo Amaldi was the general secretary of CERN at its early stages when operations were still provisional, and the first Director-General (1954) was Felix Bloch.
[src:big-science/cern] At the sixth session of the CERN Council in Paris from 29 June to 1 July 1953, the convention establishing the organization was signed, subject to ratification, by 12 states.
[src:big-science/cern] The convention was gradually ratified by the 12 founding Member States: Belgium, Denmark, France, the Federal Republic of Germany, Greece, Italy, the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and Yugoslavia.
[src:big-science/cern] Several major achievements in particle physics have occurred in experiments at CERN.
[src:big-science/cern] In September 2011, CERN attracted media attention when the OPERA Collaboration reported the detection of possibly faster-than-light neutrinos.
[src:big-science/cern] Further tests showed that the results were flawed due to an incorrectly connected GPS synchronization cable.
[src:big-science/cern] The 1984 Nobel Prize for Physics was awarded to Carlo Rubbia and Simon van der Meer for the developments that resulted in the discoveries of the W and Z bosons.
[src:big-science/cern] The 1992 Nobel Prize for Physics was awarded to CERN staff researcher Georges Charpak "for his invention and development of particle detectors, in particular the multiwire proportional chamber".
[src:big-science/cern] The 2013 Nobel Prize for Physics was awarded to François Englert and Peter Higgs for the theoretical description of the Higgs mechanism in the year after the Higgs boson was found by CERN experiments.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN pioneered the introduction of TCP/IP for its intranet, beginning in 1984.
[src:big-science/cern] This played an influential role in the adoption of the TCP/IP in Europe (see History of the Internet and Protocol Wars).
[src:big-science/cern] In 1989, the World Wide Web was invented at CERN by Tim Berners-Lee.
[src:big-science/cern] Based on the concept of hypertext, the idea was designed to facilitate information sharing between researchers.
[src:big-science/cern] This stemmed from Berners-Lee's earlier work at CERN on a database named ENQUIRE.
[src:big-science/cern] A colleague, Robert Cailliau, became involved in 1990.
[src:big-science/cern] In 1995, Berners-Lee and Cailliau were jointly honoured by the Association for Computing Machinery for their contributions to the development of the World Wide Web.
[src:big-science/cern] A copy of the first webpage, created by Berners-Lee, is still published on the World Wide Web Consortium's website as a historical document.
[src:big-science/cern] The first website was activated in 1991.
[src:big-science/cern] On 30 April 1993, CERN announced that the World Wide Web would be free to anyone.
[src:big-science/cern] It became the dominant way through which most users interact with the Internet.
[src:big-science/cern] More recently, CERN has become a facility for the development of grid computing, hosting projects including the Enabling Grids for E-sciencE (EGEE) and LHC Computing Grid.
[src:big-science/cern] It also hosts the CERN Internet Exchange Point (CIXP), one of the two main internet exchange points in Switzerland.
[src:big-science/cern] As of 2022, CERN employs ten times more engineers and technicians than research physicists.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN operates a network of seven accelerators and two decelerators, and some additional small accelerators.
[src:big-science/cern] Each machine in the chain increases the energy of particle beams before delivering them to experiments or to the next more powerful accelerator.
[src:big-science/cern] The decelerators naturally decrease the energy of particle beams before delivering them to experiments or further accelerators/decelerators.
[src:big-science/cern] Before an experiment is able to use the network of accelerators, it must be approved by the various Scientific Committees of CERN.
[src:big-science/cern] Many activities at CERN currently involve operating the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) and the experiments for it.
[src:big-science/cern] The LHC represents a large-scale, worldwide scientific cooperation project.
[src:big-science/cern] The LHC tunnel is located 100 metres underground, in the region between Geneva International Airport and the nearby Jura mountains.
[src:big-science/cern] The majority of its length is on the French side of the border.
[src:big-science/cern] It uses the 27 km circumference circular tunnel previously occupied by the Large Electron–Positron Collider (LEP), which was shut down in November 2000.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN's existing PS/SPS accelerator complexes are used to pre-accelerate protons and lead ions which are then injected into the LHC.
[src:big-science/cern] Eight experiments (CMS, ATLAS, LHCb, MoEDAL, TOTEM, LHCf, FASER and ALICE) are located along the collider; each of them studies particle collisions from a different aspect, and with different technologies.
[src:big-science/cern] Construction for these experiments required an extraordinary engineering effort.
[src:big-science/cern] For example, a special crane was rented from Belgium to lower pieces of the CMS detector into its cavern, since each piece weighed nearly 2000 tons.
[src:big-science/cern] The first of the approximately 5000 magnets necessary for construction was lowered down a special shaft at in March 2005.
[src:big-science/cern] The LHC has begun to generate vast quantities of data, which CERN streams to laboratories around the world for distributed processing, making use of a specialized grid infrastructure, the LHC Computing Grid.
[src:big-science/cern] In April 2005, a trial successfully streamed 600 MB/s to seven different sites across the world.
[src:big-science/cern] In August 2008, the initial particle beams were injected into the LHC.
[src:big-science/cern] The first beam was circulated through the entire LHC on 10 September 2008, but the system failed 10 days later because of a faulty magnet connection, and it was stopped for repairs on 19 September 2008.
[src:big-science/cern] The LHC resumed operation on 20 November 2009 by successfully circulating two beams, each with an energy of 3.5 teraelectronvolts (TeV).
[src:big-science/cern] The challenge for the engineers was then to line up the two beams so that they smashed into each other.
[src:big-science/cern] This is like "firing two needles across the Atlantic and getting them to hit each other" according to Stephen Myers, director for accelerators and technology.
[src:big-science/cern] On 30 March 2010, the LHC successfully collided two proton beams with 3.5 TeV of energy per proton, resulting in a 7 TeV collision energy.
[src:big-science/cern] This was enough to start the main research program, including the search for the Higgs boson.
[src:big-science/cern] When the 7 TeV experimental period ended, the LHC increased to 8 TeV (4 TeV per proton) starting March 2012, and soon began particle collisions at that energy.
[src:big-science/cern] In July 2012, CERN scientists announced the discovery of a new sub-atomic particle that was later confirmed to be the Higgs boson.
[src:big-science/cern] In March 2013, CERN announced that the measurements performed on the newly found particle allowed it to conclude that it was a Higgs boson.
[src:big-science/cern] In early 2013, the LHC was deactivated for a two-year maintenance period, to strengthen the electrical connections between magnets inside the accelerator and for other upgrades.
[src:big-science/cern] On 5 April 2015, after two years of maintenance and consolidation, the LHC restarted for a second run.
[src:big-science/cern] The first ramp to the record-breaking energy of 6.5 TeV was performed on 10 April 2015.
[src:big-science/cern] In 2016, the design collision rate was exceeded for the first time.
[src:big-science/cern] A second two-year period of shutdown begun at the end of 2018.
[src:big-science/cern] Following its final run on June 14 2026, the accelerator was switched off to begin CERN’s Long Shutdown 3 (LS3).
[src:big-science/cern] This programme will focus on maintenance and upgrades in preparation for the Laboratory for the High-Luminosity LHC (HiLumi LHC), which is scheduled to be operational by the mid-2030s.
[src:big-science/cern] As of October 2019, the construction is on-going to upgrade the LHC's luminosity in a project called High Luminosity LHC (HL–LHC).
[src:big-science/cern] This project should see the LHC accelerator upgraded by 2026 to an order of magnitude higher luminosity.
[src:big-science/cern] As part of the HL–LHC upgrade project, also other CERN accelerators and their subsystems are receiving upgrades.
[src:big-science/cern] Among other work, the LINAC 2 linear accelerator injector was decommissioned and replaced by a new injector accelerator, the LINAC4.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN, in collaboration with groups worldwide, is investigating two main concepts for future accelerators: A linear electron-positron collider with a new acceleration concept to increase the energy (CLIC) and a larger version of the LHC, a project currently named Future Circular Collider.
[src:big-science/cern] The smaller accelerators are on the main Meyrin site, also known as the West Area, which was originally built in Switzerland alongside the French border, but has been extended to span the border since 1965.
[src:big-science/cern] The French side is under Swiss jurisdiction and there is no obvious border within the site, apart from a line of marker stones.
[src:big-science/cern] The SPS and LEP/LHC tunnels are almost entirely outside the main site, and are mostly buried under French farmland and invisible from the surface.
[src:big-science/cern] They have surface sites at points around them, either as the location of buildings associated with experiments or other facilities needed to operate the colliders such as cryogenic plants and access shafts.
[src:big-science/cern] The experiments are located at the same underground level as the tunnels at these sites.
[src:big-science/cern] Three of these experimental sites are in France, with ATLAS in Switzerland, and some of the ancillary cryogenic and access sites are in Switzerland.
[src:big-science/cern] The largest of the experimental sites is the Prévessin site, also known as the North Area, which is the target station for non-collider experiments on the SPS accelerator.
[src:big-science/cern] Other sites are the ones which were used for the UA1, UA2 and the LEP experiments.
[src:big-science/cern] Outside of the LEP and LHC experiments, most are officially named and numbered after the site where they were located.
[src:big-science/cern] For example, NA32 was an experiment looking at the production of so-called "charmed" particles and located at the Prévessin (North Area) site.
[src:big-science/cern] WA22 used the Big European Bubble Chamber (BEBC) at the Meyrin (West Area) site to examine neutrino interactions.
[src:big-science/cern] The UA1 and UA2 experiments were considered to be in the Underground Area, i.e. situated underground at sites on the SPS accelerator.
[src:big-science/cern] Most of the roads on the CERN Meyrin and Prévessin sites are named after famous physicists, such as Niels Bohr, who pushed for CERN's creation.
[src:big-science/cern] Other notable names are Richard Feynman, Albert Einstein, and Wolfgang Pauli.
[src:big-science/cern] Since its foundation by 12 members in 1954, CERN regularly accepted new members.
[src:big-science/cern] All new members have remained in the organization continuously since their accession, except Spain and Yugoslavia.
[src:big-science/cern] Spain first joined CERN in 1961, withdrew in 1969, and rejoined in 1983.
[src:big-science/cern] Yugoslavia was a founding member of CERN but quit in 1961.
[src:big-science/cern] Of the 24 members, Israel joined CERN as a full member in January 2014, becoming the first, and currently only, non-geographically European full member.
[src:big-science/cern] The budget contributions of member states are computed based on their Net National Income at factor cost.
[src:big-science/cern] 12 founding members drafted the *Convention for the Establishment of a European Organization for Nuclear Research* which entered into force on 29 September 1954.
[src:big-science/cern] Yugoslavia left the organization in 1961.
[src:big-science/cern] Acceded members become CERN member states by ratifying the CERN convention.
[src:big-science/cern] The contribution of Ukraine for the years 2023 - 2025 have been waived and were covered by the member states through an increase of their contributions proportional to their nominal share.
[src:big-science/cern] International research institutions, such as CERN, can aid in science diplomacy.
[src:big-science/cern] A large number of institutes around the world are associated to CERN through current collaboration agreements and/or historical links.
[src:big-science/cern] The Open Science movement focuses on making scientific research openly accessible and on creating knowledge through open tools and processes.
[src:big-science/cern] Open access, open data, open source software and hardware, open licenses, digital preservation and reproducible research are primary components of open science and areas in which CERN has been working towards since its formation.
[src:big-science/cern] Since the late 1950s, the CERN Scientific Information Service was involved in distributing preprints.
[src:big-science/cern] Notably, the librarian Luisella Goldschmidt-Clermont played an important role in transforming the existing culture of personal sharing of research results into a more institutional approach and therefore lying the groundwork for what has only later been called open science.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN has developed policies and official documents that enable and promote open science, starting with CERN's founding convention in 1953 which indicated that all its results are to be published or made generally available.
[src:big-science/cern] Since then, CERN published its open access policy in 2014, which ensures that all publications by CERN authors will be published with gold open access and most recently an open data policy that was endorsed by the four main LHC collaborations (ALICE, ATLAS, CMS and LHCb).
[src:big-science/cern] The open data policy complements the open access policy, addressing the public release of scientific data collected by LHC experiments after a suitable embargo period.
[src:big-science/cern] Prior to this open data policy, guidelines for data preservation, access and reuse were implemented by each collaboration individually through their own policies which are updated when necessary.
[src:big-science/cern] Beyond the policy level, CERN has established a variety of services and tools to enable and guide open science at CERN, and in particle physics more generally.
[src:big-science/cern] On the publishing side, CERN has initiated and operates a global cooperative project, the Sponsoring Consortium for Open Access Publishing in Particle Physics, SCOAP3, to convert scientific articles in high-energy physics to open access.
[src:big-science/cern] In 2018, the SCOAP3 partnership represented 3,000+ libraries from 44 countries and 3 intergovernmental organizations who have worked collectively to convert research articles in high-energy physics across 11 leading journals in the discipline to open access.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN's efforts towards preservation and reproducible research are best represented by a suite of services addressing the entire physics analysis lifecycle, such as data, software and computing environment.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN Analysis Preservation helps researchers to preserve and document the various components of their physics analyses.
[src:big-science/cern] REANA (Reusable Analyses) enables the instantiating of preserved research data analyses on the cloud.
[src:big-science/cern] All services are built using open source software and strive towards compliance with best effort principles, such as the FAIR principles, the FORCE11 guidelines and Plan S, while taking into account relevant activities carried out by the European Commission.
[src:big-science/cern] The first public exhibition at CERN was the Microcosm museum which hosted an exhibition about particle physics and CERN history.
[src:big-science/cern] It closed permanently on 18 September 2022, in preparation for the installation of the exhibitions in the newly built science center CERN Science Gateway.
[src:big-science/cern] The CERN Science Gateway, constructed by the Renzo Piano building workshop was opened in October 2023.
[src:big-science/cern] The Globe of Science and Innovation, which opened in late 2005, is open to the public.
[src:big-science/cern] It is used four times a week for special exhibits.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN also provides daily tours to certain facilities such as the Synchro-cyclotron (CERNs first particle accelerator) and the superconducting magnet workshop.
[src:big-science/cern] CERN launched its Cultural Policy for engaging with the arts in 2011.
[src:big-science/cern] The initiative provided the essential framework and foundations for establishing Arts at CERN, the arts programme of the Laboratory.
[src:big-science/cern] Since 2012, Arts at CERN has fostered creative dialogue between art and physics through residencies, art commissions, exhibitions and events.
[src:big-science/cern] Artists across all creative disciplines have been invited to CERN to experience how fundamental science pursues the big questions about our universe.
[src:big-science/cern] Even before the arts programme officially started, several highly regarded artists visited the laboratory, drawn to physics and fundamental science.
[src:big-science/cern] In 1972, James Lee Byars was the first artist to visit the laboratory and the only one, so far, to feature on the cover of the CERN Courier.
[src:big-science/cern] Mariko Mori, Gianni Motti, Cerith Wyn Evans, John Berger and Anselm Kiefer are among the artists who came to CERN in the years that followed.
[src:big-science/cern] The programmes of Arts at CERN are structured according to their values and vision to create bridges between cultures.
[src:big-science/cern] Each programme is designed and formed in collaboration with cultural institutions, other partner laboratories, countries, cities and artistic communities eager to connect with CERN's research, support their activities, and contribute to a global network of art and science.
[src:big-science/cern] They comprise research-led artistic residencies that take place on-site or remotely.
[src:big-science/cern] More than 200 artists from 80 countries have participated in the residencies to expand their creative practices at the Laboratory, benefiting from the involvement of 400 physicists, engineers and CERN staff.
[src:big-science/cern] Between 500 and 800 applications are received every year.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The **Cold War** was a period of international geopolitical rivalry between the United States (US) and the Soviet Union (USSR) and their respective allies, the capitalist Western Bloc and communist Eastern Bloc.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] It began in the aftermath of the Second World War and ended with the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The term *cold war* is used because there was no direct fighting between the two superpowers, though each supported opposing sides in regional conflicts known as proxy wars.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In addition to the struggle for ideological and economic influence and an arms race in both conventional and nuclear weapons, the Cold War was expressed through technological rivalries such as the Space Race, espionage, propaganda campaigns, embargoes, and sports diplomacy.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] After the end of the Second World War in 1945, during which the US and USSR had been allies, the USSR installed satellite governments in its occupied territories in Eastern Europe and North Korea by 1949, resulting in the political division of Europe (and Germany) by an "Iron Curtain".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The USSR tested its first nuclear weapon in 1949, four years after their use by the US on Hiroshima and Nagasaki, and allied with the People's Republic of China, founded in 1949.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The US declared the Truman Doctrine of "containment" of communism in 1947, launched the Marshall Plan in 1948 to assist Western Europe's economic recovery, and founded the NATO military alliance in 1949 (matched by the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact in 1955).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Berlin Blockade of 1948 to 1949 was an early confrontation, as was the Korean War of 1950 to 1953, which ended in a stalemate.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] US involvement in regime change during the Cold War included support for First World anti-communist and right-wing dictatorships and uprisings, while Soviet involvement included the funding of Second World left-wing parties, wars of independence, and dictatorships.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] As nearly all the colonial states underwent decolonization, many became Third World battlefields of the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Both powers used economic aid in an attempt to win the loyalty of non-aligned countries.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Cuban Revolution of 1959 installed the first communist regime in the Western Hemisphere, and in 1962, the Cuban Missile Crisis began after deployments of US missiles in Europe and Soviet missiles in Cuba; it is widely considered the closest the Cold War came to escalating into nuclear war.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Another major proxy conflict was the Vietnam War of 1955 to 1975, which ended in defeat for the US.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The USSR solidified its domination of Eastern Europe with its crushing of the Hungarian Revolution in 1956 and the Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Relations between the USSR and China broke down by 1961, with the Sino-Soviet split bringing the two states to the brink of war amid a border conflict in 1969.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In 1972, the US initiated diplomatic contacts with China and the US and USSR signed a series of treaties limiting their nuclear arsenals during a period known as détente.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In 1979, the toppling of US-allied governments in Iran and Nicaragua and the outbreak of the Soviet–Afghan War again raised tensions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In 1985, Mikhail Gorbachev became leader of the USSR and expanded political freedoms, which contributed to the revolutions of 1989 in the Eastern Bloc and the collapse of the USSR in 1991, ending the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Writer George Orwell used *cold war*, as a general term, in his essay "You and the Atomic Bomb", published 19 October 1945.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The first use of the term to describe the specific post-war geopolitical confrontation between the Soviet Union and the United States came in a speech by Bernard Baruch, an influential advisor to Democratic presidents, on 16 April 1947.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The speech, written by journalist Herbert Bayard Swope, proclaimed, "we are today in the midst of a cold war." Newspaper columnist Walter Lippmann gave the term wide currency with his book *The Cold War*.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] When asked in 1947 about the source of the term, Lippmann traced it to a French term from the 1930s, *la guerre froide*.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The United States and its Western European allies sought to strengthen their bonds and used the policy of containment against Soviet influence; they accomplished this most notably through the formation of NATO, which was essentially a defensive agreement in 1949.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Soviet Union countered with the Warsaw Pact in 1955, which had similar results with the Eastern Bloc.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] As by that time the Soviet Union already had an armed presence and political domination all over its eastern satellite states, the pact has been long considered superfluous.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In 1961, Soviet-allied East Germany constructed the Berlin Wall to prevent the citizens of East Berlin from fleeing to West Berlin, at the time part of United States-allied West Germany.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In 1991, the Russian Federation became the Soviet Union's successor state, while many of the other republics emerged as fully independent post-Soviet states.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Kennan's "Long Telegram" from Moscow to Washington helped to articulate the US government's increasingly hard line against the Soviets, which would become the basis for US strategy toward the Soviet Union.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The telegram galvanized a policy debate that would eventually shape the Truman administration's Soviet policy.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Washington's opposition to the Soviets accumulated after broken promises by Stalin and Molotov concerning Europe and Iran.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Following the World War II Anglo-Soviet invasion of Iran, the country was occupied by the Red Army in the far north and the British in the south.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Iran was used by the United States and British to supply the Soviet Union, and the Allies agreed to withdraw from Iran within six months after the cessation of hostilities.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] However, when this deadline came, the Soviets remained in Iran under the guise of the Azerbaijan People's Government and Kurdish Republic of Mahabad.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] On 5 March, former British prime minister Winston Churchill delivered his famous "Iron Curtain" speech (Fulton Speech) calling for an Anglo-American alliance against the Soviets, whom he accused of establishing an "iron curtain" dividing Europe.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Soviet territorial demands to Turkey regarding the Dardanelles in the Turkish Straits crisis and Black Sea border disputes were also a major factor in increasing tensions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Byrnes delivered a speech in Germany repudiating the Morgenthau Plan (a proposal to partition and de-industrialize post-war Germany) and warning the Soviets that the US intended to maintain a military presence in Europe indefinitely.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] As Byrnes stated a month later, "The nub of our program was to win the German people ... it was a battle between us and Russia over minds ..." In December, the Soviets agreed to withdraw from Iran after persistent US pressure, an early success of containment policy.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Truman was outraged by the perceived resistance of the Soviet Union to American demands in Iran, Turkey, and Greece, as well as Soviet rejection of the Baruch Plan on nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In February 1947, the British government announced that it could no longer afford to finance the Kingdom of Greece against the Communist-led DSE in the Greek Civil War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In the same month, Stalin conducted the rigged 1947 Polish legislative election which constituted an open breach of the Yalta Agreement.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The US government responded by adopting a policy of containment, with the goal of stopping the spread of communism.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Truman delivered a speech calling for the allocation of $400 million to intervene in the war and unveiled the Truman Doctrine, which framed the conflict as a contest between free peoples and totalitarian regimes.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] American policymakers accused the Soviet Union of conspiring against the Greek royalists in an effort to expand Soviet influence even though Stalin had told the Communist Party to cooperate with the British-backed government.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Enunciation of the Truman Doctrine marked the beginning of a US bipartisan defense and foreign policy consensus between Republicans and Democrats focused on containment and deterrence that weakened during and after the Vietnam War, but ultimately persisted thereafter.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Other critiques of the consensus policy came from anti-Vietnam War activists, the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, and the anti-nuclear movement.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In early 1947, France, Britain and the United States unsuccessfully attempted to reach an agreement with the Soviet Union for a plan envisioning an economically self-sufficient Germany, including a detailed accounting of the industrial plants, goods and infrastructure already taken by the Soviets.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In June 1947, in accordance with the Truman Doctrine, the United States enacted the Marshall Plan, a pledge of economic assistance for all European countries willing to participate.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Under the plan, which President Harry S.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Truman signed on 3 April 1948, the US government gave to Western European countries over $13 billion (equivalent to $189 billion in 2016).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Later, the program led to the creation of the OECD.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The plan's aim was to rebuild the democratic and economic systems of Europe and to counter perceived threats to the European balance of power, such as communist parties seizing control.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The plan also stated that European prosperity was contingent upon German economic recovery.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] One month later, Truman signed the National Security Act of 1947, creating a unified Department of Defense, the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), and the National Security Council (NSC).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] These would become the main bureaucracies for US defense policy in the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Stalin believed economic integration with the West would allow Eastern Bloc countries to escape Soviet control, and that the US was trying to buy a pro-US re-alignment of Europe.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Stalin therefore prevented Eastern Bloc nations from receiving Marshall Plan aid.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Soviet Union's alternative to the Marshall Plan, which was purported to involve Soviet subsidies and trade with central and eastern Europe, became known as the Molotov Plan (later institutionalized in January 1949 as the Council for Mutual Economic Assistance).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Stalin was also fearful of a reconstituted Germany; his vision of a post-war Germany did not include the ability to rearm or pose any kind of threat to the Soviet Union.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In early 1948, Czech Communists executed a coup d'état in Czechoslovakia (resulting in the formation of the Czechoslovak Socialist Republic), the only Eastern Bloc state that the Soviets had permitted to retain democratic structures.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The public brutality of the coup shocked Western powers more than any event up to that point and swept away the last vestiges of opposition to the Marshall Plan in the United States Congress.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The twin policies of the Truman Doctrine and the Marshall Plan led to billions in economic and military aid for Western Europe, Greece, and Turkey.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] With the US assistance, the Greek military won its civil war.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Under the leadership of Alcide De Gasperi the Italian Christian Democrats defeated the powerful Communist–Socialist alliance in the elections of 1948.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Outside of Europe, the United States also began to express interest in the development of many other countries, so that they would not fall under the sway of Eastern Bloc communism.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In his January 1949 inaugural address, Truman declared for the first time in US history that international development would be a key part of US foreign policy.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The resulting program later became known as the Point Four Program because it was the fourth point raised in his address.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] All major powers engaged in espionage, using a great variety of spies, double agents, moles, and new technologies such as the tapping of telephone cables.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Soviet KGB ("Committee for State Security"), the bureau responsible for foreign espionage and internal surveillance, was famous for its effectiveness.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The most famous Soviet operation involved its atomic spies that delivered crucial information from the United States' Manhattan Project, leading the USSR to detonate its first nuclear weapon in 1949, four years after the American detonation and much sooner than expected.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] A massive network of informants throughout the Soviet Union was used to monitor dissent from official Soviet politics and morals.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Although to an extent disinformation had always existed, the term itself was invented, and the strategy formalized by a black propaganda department of the Soviet KGB.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Based on the amount of top-secret Cold War archival information that has been released, historian Raymond L.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Garthoff concludes there probably was parity in the quantity and quality of secret information obtained by each side.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Benson, "Washington's forte was 'signals' intelligence – the procurement and analysis of coded foreign messages," leading to the Venona project or Venona intercepts, which monitored the communications of Soviet intelligence agents.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Moynihan wrote that the Venona project contained "overwhelming proof of the activities of Soviet spy networks in America, complete with names, dates, places, and deeds." The Venona project was kept highly secret even from policymakers until the Moynihan Commission in 1995.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Despite this, the decryption project had already been betrayed and dispatched to the USSR by Kim Philby and Bill Weisband in 1946, as was discovered by the US by 1950.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Nonetheless, the Soviets had to keep their discovery of the program secret, too, and continued leaking their own information, some of which was still useful to the American program.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] According to Moynihan, even President Truman may not have been fully informed of Venona, which may have left him unaware of the extent of Soviet espionage.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Clandestine atomic spies from the Soviet Union, who infiltrated the Manhattan Project during WWII, played a major role in increasing tensions that led to the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In addition to usual espionage, the Western agencies paid special attention to debriefing Eastern Bloc defectors.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Edward Jay Epstein describes that the CIA understood that the KGB used "provocations", or fake defections, as a trick to embarrass Western intelligence and establish Soviet double agents.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] As a result, from 1959 to 1973, the CIA required that East Bloc defectors went through a counterintelligence investigation before being recruited as a source of intelligence.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] During the late 1970s and 1980s, the KGB perfected its use of espionage to sway and distort diplomacy.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Active measures were "clandestine operations designed to further Soviet foreign policy goals," consisting of disinformation, forgeries, leaks to foreign media, and the channeling of aid to militant groups.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] During the Sino-Soviet split, "spy wars" also occurred between the USSR and PRC.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In September 1947, the Soviets created Cominform to impose orthodoxy within the international communist movement and tighten political control over Soviet satellites through coordination of communist parties in the Eastern Bloc.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Cominform faced an embarrassing setback the following June, when the Tito–Stalin split obliged its members to expel Yugoslavia, which remained communist but adopted a non-aligned position and began accepting financial aid from the US.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Besides Berlin, the status of the city of Trieste was at issue.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Until the break between Tito and Stalin, the Western powers and the Eastern bloc faced each other uncompromisingly.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In addition to capitalism and communism, Italians and Slovenes, monarchists and republicans as well as war winners and losers often faced each other irreconcilably.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The neutral buffer state Free Territory of Trieste, founded in 1947 with the United Nations, was split up and dissolved in 1954 and 1975, also because of the détente between the West and Tito.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The US and Britain merged their western German occupation zones into "Bizone" (1 January 1947, later "Trizone" with the addition of France's zone, April 1949).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] As part of the economic rebuilding of Germany, in early 1948, representatives of a number of Western European governments and the United States announced an agreement for a merger of western German areas into a federal governmental system.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In addition, in accordance with the Marshall Plan, they began to re-industrialize and rebuild the West German economy, including the introduction of a new Deutsche Mark currency to replace the old Reichsmark currency that the Soviets had debased.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Shortly thereafter, Stalin instituted the Berlin Blockade (June 1948 – May 1949), one of the first major crises of the Cold War, preventing Western supplies from reaching West Germany's enclave of West Berlin.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The United States (primarily), Britain, France, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and several other countries began the massive "Berlin airlift", supplying West Berlin with provisions despite Soviet threats.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Soviets mounted a public relations campaign against the policy change.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Once again, the East Berlin communists attempted to disrupt the Berlin municipal elections, which were held on 5 December 1948 and produced a turnout of 86% and an overwhelming victory for the non-communist parties.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The results effectively divided the city into East and West, the latter comprising US, British and French sectors.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] 300,000 Berliners demonstrated and urged the international airlift to continue, and US Air Force pilot Gail Halvorsen created "Operation Vittles", which supplied candy to German children.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Airlift was as much a logistical as a political and psychological success for the West; it firmly linked West Berlin to the United States.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In May 1949, Stalin lifted the blockade.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In 1952, Stalin repeatedly proposed a plan to unify East and West Germany under a single government chosen in elections supervised by the United Nations, if the new Germany were to stay out of Western military alliances, but this proposal was turned down by the Western powers.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Some sources dispute the sincerity of the proposal.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Britain, France, the United States, Canada, and eight other Western European countries signed the North Atlantic Treaty of April 1949, establishing the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] That August, the first Soviet atomic device was detonated in Semipalatinsk, Kazakh SSR.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Following Soviet refusals to participate in a German rebuilding effort set forth by western European countries in 1948, the US, Britain and France spearheaded the establishment of the Federal Republic of Germany from the three Western zones of occupation in April 1949.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Soviet Union proclaimed its zone of occupation in Germany the German Democratic Republic that October.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Media in the Eastern Bloc was an organ of the state, completely reliant on and subservient to the communist party.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Radio and television organizations were state-owned, while print media was usually owned by political organizations, mostly by the local communist party.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Soviet radio broadcasts used Marxist rhetoric to attack capitalism, emphasizing themes of labor exploitation, imperialism and war-mongering.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Along with the broadcasts of the BBC and the Voice of America to Central and Eastern Europe, a major propaganda effort began in 1949 was Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty, dedicated to bringing about the peaceful demise of the communist system in the Eastern Bloc.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Radio Free Europe attempted to achieve these goals by serving as a surrogate home radio station, an alternative to the controlled and party-dominated domestic press in the Soviet Bloc.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Radio Free Europe was a product of some of the most prominent architects of America's early Cold War strategy, especially those who believed that the Cold War would eventually be fought by political rather than military means, such as George F.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Soviet and Eastern Bloc authorities used various methods to suppress Western broadcasts, including radio jamming.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] American policymakers, including Kennan and John Foster Dulles, acknowledged that the Cold War was in its essence a war of ideas.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The United States, acting through the CIA, funded a long list of projects to counter the communist appeal among intellectuals in Europe and the developing world.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The CIA also covertly sponsored a domestic propaganda campaign called Crusade for Freedom.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The rearmament of West Germany was achieved in the early 1950s.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Its main promoter was Konrad Adenauer, the chancellor of West Germany, with France the main opponent.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] It was strongly supported by the Pentagon (the US military leadership), and weakly opposed by President Truman; the State Department was ambivalent.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The outbreak of the Korean War in June 1950 changed the calculations and Washington now gave full support.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Eisenhower in charge of NATO forces and sending more American troops to West Germany.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] There was a strong promise that West Germany would not develop nuclear weapons.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Widespread fears of another rise of German militarism necessitated the new military to operate within an alliance framework under NATO command.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In 1955, Washington secured full German membership of NATO.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In May 1953, Lavrentiy Beria, by then in a government post, had made an unsuccessful proposal to allow the reunification of a neutral Germany to prevent West Germany's incorporation into NATO, but his attempts were cut short after he was executed several months later during a Soviet power struggle.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The events led to the establishment of the *Bundeswehr*, the West German military, in 1955.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In 1949, Mao Zedong's People's Liberation Army defeated Chiang Kai-shek's United States-backed Kuomintang (KMT) Nationalist Government in China.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The KMT-controlled territory was now restricted to the island of Taiwan, the nationalist government of which exists to this day.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Kremlin promptly created an alliance with the newly formed People's Republic of China.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] According to Norwegian historian Odd Arne Westad, the communists won the Civil War because they made fewer military mistakes than Chiang Kai-Shek made, and because in his search for a powerful centralized government, Chiang antagonized too many interest groups in China.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Moreover, his party was weakened during the war against Japan.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Meanwhile, the communists told different groups, such as the peasants, exactly what they wanted to hear, and they cloaked themselves under the cover of Chinese nationalism.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Confronted with the communist revolution in China and the end of the American atomic monopoly in 1949, the Truman administration quickly moved to escalate and expand its containment doctrine.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In NSC 68, a secret 1950 document, the National Security Council proposed reinforcing pro-Western alliance systems and quadrupling spending on defense.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Truman, under the influence of advisor Paul Nitze, saw containment as implying complete rollback of Soviet influence in all its forms.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] United States officials moved to expand this version of containment into Asia, Africa, and Latin America, in order to counter revolutionary nationalist movements, often led by communist parties financed by the USSR.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In this way, this US would exercise "preponderant power," oppose neutrality, and establish global hegemony.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] One of the more significant examples of the implementation of containment was the United Nations US-led intervention in the Korean War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] In June 1950, after years of mutual hostilities, Kim Il Sung's North Korean People's Army invaded South Korea.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Stalin had been reluctant to support the invasion but ultimately sent advisers.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] To Stalin's surprise, the United Nations Security Council backed the defense of South Korea, although the Soviets were then boycotting meetings in protest of the fact that Taiwan (Republic of China), not the People's Republic of China, held a permanent seat on the council.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] A UN force of sixteen countries faced North Korea, although 40 percent of troops were South Korean, and about 50 percent were from the United States.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The US initially seemed to follow containment, only pushing back North Korea across the 38th Parallel and restoring South Korea's sovereignty while allowing North Korea's survival as a state.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] However, the success of the Inchon landing inspired the US/UN forces to pursue a rollback strategy instead and to overthrow communist North Korea, thereby allowing nationwide elections under UN auspices.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] General Douglas MacArthur then advanced into North Korea.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Chinese, fearful of a possible US invasion, sent in a large army and pushed the UN forces back below the 38th parallel.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The episode was used to support the wisdom of the containment doctrine as opposed to rollback.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Communists were later pushed to roughly around the original border, with minimal changes.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] Among other effects, the Korean War galvanised NATO to develop a military structure.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p01] The Korean Armistice Agreement was approved in July 1953.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1953, changes in political leadership on both sides shifted the dynamic of the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Eisenhower was inaugurated president that January.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] During the last 18 months of the Truman administration, the American defense budget had quadrupled, and Eisenhower moved to reduce military spending by a third while continuing to fight the Cold War effectively.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Nikita Khrushchev eventually won the ensuing power struggle by the mid-1950s.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1956, he denounced Joseph Stalin and proceeded to ease controls over the party and society (de-Stalinization).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] On 18 November 1956, while addressing Western dignitaries at a reception in Moscow's Polish embassy, Khrushchev infamously declared, "Whether you like it or not, history is on our side.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] We will bury you", shocking everyone present.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Eisenhower's secretary of state, John Foster Dulles, initiated a "New Look" for the containment strategy, calling for a greater reliance on nuclear weapons against US enemies in wartime.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Dulles also enunciated the doctrine of "massive retaliation", threatening a severe US response to any Soviet aggression.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Possessing nuclear superiority, for example, allowed Eisenhower to face down Soviet threats to intervene in the Middle East during the 1956 Suez Crisis.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The declassified US plans for retaliatory nuclear strikes in the late 1950s included the "systematic destruction" of 1,200 major urban centers in the Soviet Bloc and China, including Moscow, East Berlin and Beijing.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In spite of these events, there were substantial hopes for détente when an upswing in diplomacy took place in 1959, including a two-week visit by Khrushchev to the US, and plans for a two-power summit for May 1960.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The latter was disturbed by the U-2 spy plane scandal, however, in which Eisenhower was caught lying about the intrusion of American surveillance aircraft into Soviet territory.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] While Stalin's death in 1953 slightly relaxed tensions, the situation in Europe remained an uneasy armed truce.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Soviets, who had already created a network of mutual assistance treaties in the Eastern Bloc by 1949, established a formal alliance therein, the Warsaw Pact, in 1955.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Hungarian Revolution of 1956 occurred shortly after Khrushchev arranged the removal of Hungary's Stalinist leader Mátyás Rákosi.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In response to a popular anti-communist uprising, the new regime formally disbanded the secret police, declared its intention to withdraw from the Warsaw Pact and pledged to re-establish free elections.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Thousands of Hungarians were killed and arrested, imprisoned and deported to the Soviet Union, and approximately 200,000 Hungarians fled Hungary.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Hungarian leader Imre Nagy and others were executed following secret trials.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] From 1957 through 1961, Khrushchev openly and repeatedly threatened the West with nuclear annihilation.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] He claimed that Soviet missile capabilities were far superior to those of the United States, capable of wiping out any American or European city.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] According to John Lewis Gaddis, Khrushchev rejected Stalin's "belief in the inevitability of war," however.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The new leader declared his ultimate goal was "peaceful coexistence".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The events in Hungary produced ideological fractures within the communist parties of the world, particularly in Western Europe, with great decline in membership, as many in both western and socialist countries felt disillusioned by the brutal Soviet response.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The communist parties in the West would never recover.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1957, Polish foreign minister Adam Rapacki proposed the Rapacki Plan for a nuclear free zone in central Europe.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Public opinion tended to be favourable in the West, but it was rejected by leaders of West Germany, Britain, France and the United States.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] They feared it would leave the powerful conventional armies of the Warsaw Pact dominant over the weaker NATO armies.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] During November 1958, Khrushchev made an unsuccessful attempt to turn all of Berlin into an independent, demilitarized "free city".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] He gave the United States, Great Britain and France a six-month ultimatum to withdraw their troops from the sectors of West Berlin, or he would transfer control of Western access rights to the East Germans.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Khrushchev earlier explained to Mao Zedong that "Berlin is the testicles of the West.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Every time I want to make the West scream, I squeeze on Berlin." NATO formally rejected the ultimatum in mid-December and Khrushchev withdrew it in return for a Geneva conference on the German question.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] President Eisenhower's New Look policy had emphasized the use of less expensive nuclear weapons to deter Soviet aggression by threatening massive nuclear attacks on all of the Soviet Union.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Nuclear weapons were much cheaper than maintaining a large standing army, so Eisenhower cut conventional forces to save money.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Kennedy implemented a new strategy known as flexible response.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] This strategy relied on conventional arms to achieve limited goals.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] As part of this policy, Kennedy expanded the United States special operations forces, elite military units that could fight unconventionally in various conflicts.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Kennedy hoped that the flexible response strategy would allow the US to counter Soviet influence without resorting to nuclear war.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] To support his new strategy, Kennedy ordered a massive increase in defense spending and a rapid build-up of the nuclear arsenal to restore the lost superiority over the Soviet Union.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In his inaugural address, Kennedy promised "to bear any burden" in the defense of liberty, and he repeatedly asked for increases in military spending and authorization of new weapons systems.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] From 1961 to 1964, the number of nuclear weapons increased by 50 percent, as did the number of B-52 bombers to deliver them.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The new ICBM force grew from 63 intercontinental ballistic missiles to 424.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] He authorized 23 new Polaris submarines, each of which carried 16 nuclear missiles.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Kennedy also called on cities to construct fallout shelters.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Nationalist movements in some countries and regions, notably Guatemala, Indonesia and Indochina, were often allied with communist groups or otherwise perceived to be unfriendly to Western interests.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In this context, the United States and the Soviet Union increasingly competed for influence by proxy in the Third World as decolonization gained momentum in the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Both sides were selling armaments to gain influence.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Kremlin saw continuing territorial losses by imperial powers as presaging the eventual victory of their ideology.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The United States used the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) to undermine neutral or hostile Third World governments and to support allied ones.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1953, President Eisenhower implemented Operation Ajax, a covert coup operation to overthrow the Iranian prime minister, Mohammad Mosaddegh.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The popularly elected Mosaddegh had been a Middle Eastern nemesis of Britain since nationalizing the British-owned Anglo-Iranian Oil Company in 1951.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Winston Churchill told the United States that Mosaddegh was "increasingly turning towards Communist influence." The pro-Western shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, assumed control as an autocratic monarch.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The shah's policies included banning the communist Tudeh Party of Iran, and general suppression of political dissent by SAVAK, the shah's domestic security and intelligence agency.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In Guatemala, a banana republic, the 1954 Guatemalan coup d'état ousted the left-wing President Jacobo Árbenz with material CIA support.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The non-aligned Indonesian government of Sukarno was faced with a major threat to its legitimacy beginning in 1956 when several regional commanders began to demand autonomy from Jakarta.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] After mediation failed, Sukarno took action to remove the dissident commanders.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In February 1958, dissident military commanders in Central Sumatra (Colonel Ahmad Husein) and North Sulawesi (Colonel Ventje Sumual) declared the Revolutionary Government of the Republic of Indonesia-Permesta Movement aimed at overthrowing the Sukarno regime.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] They were joined by many civilian politicians from the Masyumi Party, such as Sjafruddin Prawiranegara, who were opposed to the growing influence of the communist Partai Komunis Indonesia.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Due to their anti-communist rhetoric, the rebels received arms, funding, and other covert aid from the CIA until Allen Lawrence Pope, an American pilot, was shot down after a bombing raid on government-held Ambon in April 1958.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The central government responded by launching airborne and seaborne military invasions of rebel strongholds at Padang and Manado.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] By the end of 1958, the rebels were militarily defeated, and the last remaining rebel guerilla bands surrendered by August 1961.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In the Republic of the Congo, also known as Congo-Léopoldville, newly independent from Belgium since June 1960, the Congo Crisis erupted on 5 July leading to the secession of the regions Katanga and South Kasai.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] CIA-backed President Joseph Kasa-Vubu ordered the dismissal of the democratically elected Prime Minister Patrice Lumumba and the Lumumba cabinet in September over massacres by the armed forces during the invasion of South Kasai and for involving Soviets in the country.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Later the CIA-backed Colonel Mobutu Sese Seko quickly mobilized his forces to seize power through a military coup d'état, and worked with Western intelligence agencies to imprison Lumumba and hand him over to Katangan authorities who executed him by firing squad.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In British Guiana, the leftist People's Progressive Party (PPP) candidate Cheddi Jagan won the position of chief minister in a colonially administered election in 1953 but was quickly forced to resign from power after Britain's suspension of the still-dependent nation's constitution.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Embarrassed by the landslide electoral victory of Jagan's allegedly Marxist party, the British imprisoned the PPP's leadership and maneuvered the organization into a divisive rupture in 1955.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Jagan again won the colonial elections in 1957 and 1961, despite Britain's shift to a reconsideration of its view of the left-wing Jagan as a Soviet-style communist at this time.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The United States pressured the British to withhold Guyana's independence until an alternative to Jagan could be identified, supported, and brought into office.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In Malaya, the British colonialists suppressed the communist anti-colonial rebellion.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Following the watershed defeat by the communist Viet Minh rebels at the Battle of Dien Bien Phu, the French accepted a negotiated abandonment of their neo-colonial stake in Vietnam in 1954.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] On June 4, France granted full sovereignty to the anti-communist State of Vietnam, an independent country within the French Union.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] At the Geneva Conference in July, peace accords were signed, but they ultimately resulted in Vietnam being divided at the 17th parallel north between the Communist Bloc–allied North Vietnam and the Western Bloc–allied South Vietnam.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Between 1954 and 1961, Eisenhower's United States sent economic aid and military advisers to strengthen South Vietnam's government against communist efforts to destabilize it.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] China provided increased economic aid to North Vietnam in 1967–1968.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Many emerging nations of Asia, Africa, and Latin America rejected the pressure to choose sides in the East–West competition.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1955, at the Bandung Conference in Indonesia, dozens of Third World governments resolved to stay out of the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The consensus reached at Bandung culminated with the creation of the Belgrade-headquartered Non-Aligned Movement in 1961.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Meanwhile, Khrushchev broadened Moscow's policy to establish ties with India and other key neutral states.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Independence movements in the Third World transformed the post-war order into a more pluralistic world of decolonized African and Middle Eastern nations and of rising nationalism in Asia and Latin America.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] After 1956, the Sino-Soviet alliance began to break down.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Mao had defended Stalin when Khrushchev criticized him in 1956 and treated the new Soviet leader as a superficial upstart, accusing him of having lost his revolutionary edge.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] For his part, Khrushchev, disturbed by Mao's glib attitude toward nuclear war, referred to the Chinese leader as a "lunatic on a throne".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] After this, Khrushchev made many desperate attempts to reconstitute the Sino-Soviet alliance, but Mao considered it useless and denied any proposal.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Chinese-Soviet animosity spilled out in an intra-communist propaganda war.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Further on, the Soviets focused on a bitter rivalry with Mao's China for leadership of the global communist movement.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] in general, and influenced the course of the Second Vietnam War in particular.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] On the nuclear weapons front, the United States and the Soviet Union pursued nuclear rearmament and developed long-range weapons with which they could strike the territory of the other.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In August 1957, the Soviets successfully launched the world's first intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM), and in October they launched the first Earth satellite, Sputnik 1.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] This led to what became known as the Sputnik crisis.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Central Intelligence Agency described the orbit of Sputnik 1 as a "stupendous scientific achievement" and concluded that the USSR had likely perfected an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM) capable of reaching 'any desired target with accuracy'.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The launch of Sputnik inaugurated the Space Race.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] This led to a series of historic space exploration milestones, and most notably the Apollo Moon landings from 1969 by the United States, which astronaut Frank Borman later described as "just a battle in the Cold War." The public's reaction in the Soviet Union was mixed.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Soviet government limited the release of information about the lunar landing, which affected the reaction.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] A portion of the populace did not give it any attention, and another portion was angered by it.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] A major Cold War element of the Space Race was satellite reconnaissance, as well as signals intelligence to gauge which aspects of the space programs had military capabilities.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Soviet Salyut programme, conducted in the 1970s and 1980s, put a crewed space station in long term orbit; two of the successful installations to the station were covers for secret military Almaz reconnaissance stations: Salyut 3 and Salyut 5.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] During the whole duration of the cold war, the US and the USSR represented the largest and dominant space powers of the world.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Despite their fierce competition, both nations signed international space treaties in the 1960s which would limit the militarization of space.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The first research of anti-satellite weapon technology also came about during this period.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Later, the US and USSR pursued some cooperation in space as part of détente, notably the Apollo–Soyuz orbital rendezvous and docking.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In Cuba, the 26th of July Movement, led by young revolutionaries Fidel Castro and Che Guevara, seized power in the Cuban Revolution on 1 January 1959.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Although Fidel Castro's first refused to categorize his new government as socialist and repeatedly denying being a communist, Castro appointed Marxists to senior government and military positions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Cuba began negotiating for arms purchases from the Eastern Bloc in March 1960.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The same month, Eisenhower gave approval to CIA plans and funding to overthrow Castro.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In January 1961, just prior to leaving office, Eisenhower formally severed relations with the Cuban government.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] That April, the administration of newly elected American President John F.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Kennedy mounted the unsuccessful CIA-organized ship-borne invasion of the island by Cuban exiles at Playa Girón and Playa Larga in Santa Clara Province—a failure that publicly humiliated the United States.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Castro responded by publicly embracing Marxism–Leninism, and the Soviet Union pledged to provide further support.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In December, the US government began a violent campaign of terrorist attacks against civilians in Cuba, and covert operations and sabotage against the administration, in an attempt to overthrow the Cuban government.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Berlin Crisis of 1961 was the last major incident in the Cold War regarding the status of Berlin and post–World War II Germany.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] By the early 1950s, the Soviet approach to restricting emigration movement was emulated by most of the rest of the Eastern Bloc.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] However, hundreds of thousands of East Germans annually emigrated to free and prosperous West Germany through a "loophole" in the system that existed between East Berlin and West Berlin.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The emigration resulted in a massive "brain drain" from East Germany to West Germany of younger educated professionals, such that nearly 20% of East Germany's population had migrated to West Germany by 1961.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] That June, the Soviet Union issued a new ultimatum demanding the withdrawal of Allied forces from West Berlin.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The request was rebuffed, but the United States now limited its security guarantees to West Berlin.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] On 13 August, East Germany erected a barbed-wire barrier that would eventually be expanded through construction into the Berlin Wall, effectively closing the loophole and preventing its citizens from fleeing to the West.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Kennedy administration continued seeking ways to oust Castro following the Bay of Pigs invasion, experimenting with various ways of covertly facilitating the overthrow of the Cuban government.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Significant hopes were pinned on the program of terrorist attacks and other destabilization operations known as Operation Mongoose, that was devised under the Kennedy administration in 1961.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Khrushchev learned of the project in February 1962, and preparations to install Soviet nuclear missiles in Cuba were undertaken in response.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Alarmed, Kennedy considered various reactions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] He ultimately responded to the installation of nuclear missiles in Cuba with a naval blockade, and he presented an ultimatum to the Soviets.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Khrushchev backed down from a confrontation, and the Soviet Union removed the missiles in return for a public American pledge not to invade Cuba again as well as a covert deal to remove US missiles from Turkey.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Cuban Missile Crisis (October – November 1962) brought the world closer to nuclear war than ever before.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The aftermath led to efforts in the nuclear arms race at nuclear disarmament and improving relations, although the Cold War's first arms control agreement, the Antarctic Treaty, had come into force in 1961.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The compromise embarrassed Khrushchev and the Soviet Union because the withdrawal of US missiles from Italy and Turkey was a secret deal between Kennedy and Khrushchev, and the Soviets were seen as retreating from circumstances that they had started.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1964, Khrushchev's Kremlin colleagues managed to oust him, but allowed him a peaceful retirement.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] He was accused of rudeness and incompetence, and John Lewis Gaddis argues that he was also blamed with ruining Soviet agriculture, bringing the world to the brink of nuclear war, and becoming an "international embarrassment" when he authorized construction of the Berlin Wall.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] According to Dobrynin, the top Soviet leadership took the Cuban outcome as "a blow to its prestige bordering on humiliation".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In the course of the 1960s and 1970s, Cold War participants struggled to adjust to a new, more complicated pattern of international relations in which the world was no longer divided into two clearly opposed blocs.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In Indonesia, the hardline anti-communist General Suharto wrested control from predecessor Sukarno in an attempt to establish a "New Order".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] From 1965 to 1966, with the aid of the US and other Western governments, the military led the mass killing of more than 500,000 members and sympathizers of the Indonesian Communist Party and other leftist organizations, and detained hundreds of thousands in prison camps under inhumane conditions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Vietnam War descended into a quagmire for the United States, leading to a decline in international prestige and economic stability, derailing arms agreements, and provoking domestic unrest.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] America's withdrawal from the war led it to embrace a policy of détente with both China and the Soviet Union.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Backed by the Kampuchean United Front for National Salvation, an organization of Khmer pro-Soviet Communists and Khmer Rouge defectors, Vietnam invaded Cambodia on 22 December 1978.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The invasion succeeded in deposing Pol Pot, but the new state struggled to gain international recognition beyond the Soviet Bloc sphere.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Despite the international outcry at the Pol Pot regime's gross human rights violations, representatives of the Khmer Rouge were allowed to be seated in the UN General Assembly, with strong support from China, the Western powers, and the member countries of ASEAN.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Following the destruction of the Khmer Rouge, the national reconstruction of Cambodia was hampered, and Vietnam suffered a punitive Chinese attack.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Although unable to deter Vietnam from ousting Pol Pot, China demonstrated that its Cold War communist adversary, the Soviet Union, was unable to protect its Vietnamese ally.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Secretary of State Henry Kissinger wrote that "China succeeded in exposing the limits of...[Soviet] strategic reach" and speculated that the desire to "compensate for their ineffectuality" contributed to the Soviets' decision to intervene in Afghanistan a year later.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In the 1973 oil crisis, Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) cut their petroleum output.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] This raised oil prices and hurt Western economies, but helped the Soviet Union by generating a huge flow of money from its oil sales.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] As a result of the oil crisis, combined with the growing influence of Third World alignments, such as OPEC and the Non-Aligned Movement, less powerful countries had more room to assert their independence and often showed themselves resistant to pressure from either superpower.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Meanwhile, Moscow was forced to turn its attention inward to deal with the Soviet Union's deep-seated domestic economic problems.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] During this period, Soviet leaders such as Leonid Brezhnev and Alexei Kosygin embraced the notion of détente.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Kennedy, US troop levels in Vietnam grew from just under a thousand in 1959 to 16,000 in 1963.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] South Vietnamese President Ngo Dinh Diem's heavy-handed crackdown on Buddhist monks in 1963 led the US to endorse a deadly military coup against Diem.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The war escalated further in 1964 following the controversial Gulf of Tonkin incident, in which a US destroyer was alleged to have clashed with North Vietnamese fast attack craft.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Gulf of Tonkin Resolution gave President Lyndon B.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Johnson broad authorization to increase US military presence, deploying ground combat units for the first time and increasing troop levels to 184,000.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev responded by reversing Khrushchev's policy of disengagement and increasing aid to the North Vietnamese, hoping to entice the North from its pro-Chinese position.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The USSR discouraged further escalation of the war, however, providing just enough military assistance to tie up American forces.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] From this point, the People's Army of Vietnam (PAVN) engaged in more conventional warfare with US and South Vietnamese forces.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Tet Offensive of 1968 proved to be the turning point of the war.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Despite years of American tutelage and aid, the South Vietnamese forces were unable to withstand the communist offensive and the task fell to US forces instead.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] At the same time, in 1963–1965, American domestic politics saw the triumph of liberalism.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty was signed on August 5, 1963, by the United States, the Soviet Union, and over 100 other nations.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] This treaty banned nuclear weapons tests in the atmosphere, outer space, and underwater, restricting such tests to underground environments.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The treaty followed heightened concerns over the militarization of space, amplified by the United States' Starfish Prime test in 1962, which involved the detonation of a nuclear device in the upper atmosphere.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] To further delineate the peaceful use of outer space, the United Nations facilitated the drafting of the *Treaty on Principles Governing the Activities of States in the Exploration and Use of Outer Space, including the Moon and Other Celestial Bodies*, commonly known as the Outer Space Treaty.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Signed on January 27, 1967, by the United States, the Soviet Union, and the United Kingdom, it entered into force on October 10, 1967.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The treaty established space as a domain to be used exclusively for peaceful purposes, prohibiting the placement of nuclear weapons or any other weapons of mass destruction in orbit or on celestial bodies.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1968, a period of political liberalization took place in Czechoslovakia called the Prague Spring.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In answer to the Prague Spring, on 20 August 1968, the Soviet Army, together with most of their Warsaw Pact allies, invaded Czechoslovakia.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The invasion was followed by a wave of emigration, including an estimated 70,000 Czechs and Slovaks initially fleeing, with the total eventually reaching 300,000.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The invasion sparked intense protests from Yugoslavia, Romania, China, and from Western European countries.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] As a result of the Sino-Soviet split, tensions along the Chinese–Soviet border reached their peak in 1969, when the Soviet planned to launch a large-scale nuclear strike against China.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Although indirect conflict between Cold War powers continued through the late 1960s and early 1970s, tensions were beginning to ease.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Following his visit to China, Nixon met with Soviet leaders in Moscow.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] These Strategic Arms Limitation Talks resulted in landmark arms control treaties.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] These aimed to limit the development of costly anti-ballistic missiles and nuclear missiles.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Nixon and Brezhnev proclaimed a new era of "peaceful coexistence" and established the groundbreaking new policy of détente (or cooperation) between the superpowers.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Meanwhile, Brezhnev attempted to revive the Soviet economy, which was declining in part because of heavy military expenditures.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Soviet Union's military budget in the 1970s was massive, 40–60% of the federal budget and 15% of GDP.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Between 1972 and 1974, the two sides also agreed to strengthen their economic ties, including agreements for increased trade.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] As a result of their meetings, *détente* would replace the hostility of the Cold War and the two countries would live mutually.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] These developments coincided with Bonn's *Ostpolitik* policy formulated by the West German Chancellor Willy Brandt, an effort to normalize relations between West Germany and Eastern Europe.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Other agreements were concluded to stabilize the situation in Europe, culminating in the Helsinki Accords signed at the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe in 1975.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Helsinki Accords, in which the Soviets promised to grant free elections in Europe, has been called a major concession to ensure peace by the Soviets.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In practice, the Soviet government significantly curbed the rule of law, civil liberties, protection of law, and guarantees of property, which were considered examples of "bourgeois morality" by Soviet legal theorists such as Andrey Vyshinsky.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Human rights activists in the Soviet Union were regularly subjected to harassment, repressions and arrests.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The pro-Soviet American business magnate Armand Hammer of Occidental Petroleum often mediated trade relations.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Author Daniel Yergin, in his book *The Prize*, writes that Hammer "ended up as a go-between for five Soviet General Secretaries and seven US Presidents." Hammer had extensive business relationship in the Soviet Union stretching back to the 1920s with Lenin's approval.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Kissinger and Nixon were "realists" who deemphasized idealistic goals like anti-communism or promotion of democracy worldwide because those goals were too expensive in terms of America's economic capabilities.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] They rejected "idealism" as impractical and too expensive, and neither man showed much sensitivity to the plight of people living under communism.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Kissinger's realism fell out of fashion as idealism returned to American foreign policy with Carter's moralism emphasizing human rights, and Reagan's rollback strategy aimed at destroying communism.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In the 1970s, the KGB, led by Yuri Andropov, continued to persecute distinguished Soviet dissidents, such as Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn and Andrei Sakharov, who were criticising the Soviet leadership in harsh terms.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Indirect conflict between the superpowers continued through this period of détente in the Third World, particularly during political crises in the Middle East, Chile, Ethiopia, and Angola.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1973, Nixon announced his administration was committed to seeking most favored nation trade status with the USSR, which was challenged by Congress in the Jackson-Vanik Amendment.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The United States had long linked trade with the Soviet Union to its foreign policy toward the Soviet Union and, especially since the early 1980s, to Soviet human rights policies.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Jackson-Vanik Amendment, which was attached to the 1974 Trade Act, linked the granting of most-favored-nation to the USSR to the right of persecuted Soviet Jews to emigrate.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Because the Soviet Union refused the right of emigration to Jewish refuseniks, the ability of the President to apply most-favored nation trade status to the Soviet Union was restricted.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The period in the late 1970s and early 1980s showed an intensive reawakening of Cold War tensions and conflicts.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Tensions greatly increased between the major powers with both sides becoming more militant.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In April 1978, the communist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA) seized power in Afghanistan in the Saur Revolution.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Within months, opponents of the communist regime launched an uprising in eastern Afghanistan that quickly expanded into a civil war waged by guerrilla mujahideen against government forces countrywide.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Islamic Unity of Afghanistan Mujahideen insurgents received military training and weapons in neighboring Pakistan and China, while the Soviet Union sent thousands of military advisers to support the PDPA government.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Meanwhile, increasing friction between the competing factions of the PDPA—the dominant Khalq and the more moderate Parcham—resulted in the dismissal of Parchami cabinet members and the arrest of Parchami military officers under the pretext of a Parchami coup.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] By mid-1979, the United States had started a covert program to assist the mujahideen.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In September 1979, Khalqist President Nur Muhammad Taraki was assassinated in a coup within the PDPA orchestrated by fellow Khalq member Hafizullah Amin, who assumed the presidency.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Distrusted by the Soviets, Amin was assassinated by Soviet special forces during Operation Storm-333 in December 1979.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Afghan forces suffered losses during the Soviet operation; 30 Afghan palace guards and over 300 army guards were killed while another 150 were captured.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In the aftermath of the operation, a total of 1,700 Afghan soldiers who surrendered to Soviet forces were taken as prisoners, and the Soviets installed Babrak Karmal, the leader of the PDPA's Parcham faction, as Amin's successor.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Veterans of the Soviet Union's Alpha Group have stated that Operation Storm-333 was one of the most successful in the unit's history.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The PDBA was tasked to fill the vacuum and carried out a purge of Amin supporters.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Soviet troops were deployed to put Afghanistan under Soviet control with Karmal in more substantial numbers, although the Soviet government did not expect to do most of the fighting in Afghanistan.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] As a result, however, the Soviets were now directly involved in what had been a domestic war in Afghanistan.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] He described the Soviet incursion as "the most serious threat to the peace since the Second World War".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In January 1977, four years prior to becoming president, Ronald Reagan bluntly stated, in a conversation with Richard V.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Allen, his basic expectation in relation to the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] "My idea of American policy toward the Soviet Union is simple, and some would say simplistic," he said.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] "It is this: We win and they lose." In 1980, Ronald Reagan won the 1980 presidential election, vowing to increase military spending and confront the Soviets everywhere.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Both Reagan and new British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher denounced the Soviet Union and its ideology.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] It hurt the Soviet economy, but it also caused ill will among American allies in Europe who counted on that revenue.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] By early 1985, Reagan's anti-communist position had developed into a stance known as the new Reagan Doctrine—which, in addition to containment, formulated an additional right to subvert existing communist governments.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Besides continuing Carter's policy of supporting the Islamic opponents of the Soviet Union and the Soviet-backed PDPA government in Afghanistan, the CIA also sought to weaken the Soviet Union itself by promoting Islamism in the majority-Muslim Central Asian Soviet Union.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Additionally, the CIA encouraged anti-communist Pakistan's ISI to train Muslims from around the world to participate in the jihad against the Soviet Union.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Pope John Paul II provided a moral focus for anti-communism; a visit to his native Poland in 1979 stimulated a religious and nationalist resurgence centered on the Solidarity movement trade union that galvanized opposition, and may have led to his attempted assassination two years later.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In December 1981, Poland's Wojciech Jaruzelski reacted to the crisis by imposing a period of martial law.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Reagan imposed economic sanctions on Poland in response.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Mikhail Suslov, the Kremlin's top ideologist, advised Soviet leaders not to intervene if Poland fell under the control of Solidarity, for fear it might lead to heavy economic sanctions, resulting in a catastrophe for the Soviet economy.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Soviet Union had built up a military that consumed as much as 25 percent of its gross national product at the expense of consumer goods and investment in civilian sectors.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Soviet spending on the arms race and other Cold War commitments both caused and exacerbated deep-seated structural problems in the Soviet system, which experienced at least a decade of economic stagnation during the late Brezhnev years.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Soviet investment in the defense sector was not driven by military necessity but in large part by the interests of the nomenklatura, which was dependent on the sector for their own power and privileges.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Soviet Armed Forces became the largest in the world in terms of the numbers and types of weapons they possessed, in the number of troops in their ranks, and in the sheer size of their military–industrial base.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] However, the quantitative advantages held by the Soviet military often concealed areas where the Eastern Bloc dramatically lagged behind the West.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] For example, the Persian Gulf War demonstrated how the armor, fire control systems, and firing range of the Soviet Union's most common main battle tank, the T-72, were drastically inferior to the American M1 Abrams, yet the USSR fielded almost three times as many T-72s as the US deployed M1s.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] By the early 1980s, the USSR had built up a military arsenal and army surpassing that of the United States.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Soon after the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, President Carter began massively building up the United States military.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] This buildup was accelerated by the Reagan administration, which increased the military spending from 5.3 percent of GNP in 1981 to 6.5 percent in 1986, the largest peacetime defense buildup in United States history.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The American-Soviet tensions present during 1983 was defined by some as the start of "Cold War II".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] While in retrospective this phase of the Cold War was generally defined as a "war of words", the Soviet's "peace offensive" was largely rejected by the West.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Soviets deployed RSD-10 Pioneer ballistic missiles targeting Western Europe, and NATO decided, under the impetus of the Carter presidency, to deploy MGM-31 Pershing and cruise missiles in Europe, primarily West Germany.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] This deployment placed missiles just 10 minutes' striking distance from Moscow.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] After Reagan's military buildup, the Soviet Union did not respond by further building its military, because the enormous military expenses, along with inefficient planned manufacturing and collectivized agriculture, were already a heavy burden for the Soviet economy.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] At the same time, Saudi Arabia increased oil production, even as other non-OPEC nations were increasing production.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] These developments contributed to the 1980s oil glut, which affected the Soviet Union as oil was the main source of Soviet export revenues.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Issues with command economics, oil price decreases and large military expenditures gradually brought the Soviet economy to stagnation.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] On 1 September 1983, the Soviet Union shot down Korean Air Lines Flight 007, a Boeing 747 with 269 people aboard, including sitting Congressman Larry McDonald, an action which Reagan characterized as a massacre.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The airliner was en route from Anchorage to Seoul but owing to a navigational mistake made by the crew, it flew through Russian prohibited airspace.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Soviet Air Force treated the unidentified aircraft as an intruding U.S. spy plane and destroyed it with air-to-air missiles.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The incident increased support for military deployment, overseen by Reagan, which stood in place until the later accords between Reagan and Mikhail Gorbachev.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] As such, he has been credited as "the man who saved the world".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Able Archer 83 exercise in November 1983, a realistic simulation of a coordinated NATO nuclear release, was perhaps the most dangerous moment since the Cuban Missile Crisis, as the Soviet leadership feared that a nuclear attack might be imminent.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] American domestic public concerns about intervening in foreign conflicts persisted from the end of the Vietnam War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Reagan administration emphasized the use of quick, low-cost counterinsurgency tactics to intervene in foreign conflicts.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] In 1983, the Reagan administration intervened in the multisided Lebanese Civil War, invaded Grenada, bombed Libya and backed the Central American Contras, anti-communist paramilitaries seeking to overthrow the Soviet-aligned Sandinista government in Nicaragua.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] While Reagan's interventions against Grenada and Libya were popular in the United States, his backing of the Contra rebels was mired in controversy.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Reagan administration's backing of the military government of Guatemala during the Guatemalan Civil War, in particular the regime of Efraín Ríos Montt, was also controversial.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Meanwhile, the Soviets incurred high costs for their own foreign interventions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] Although Brezhnev was convinced in 1979 that the Soviet war in Afghanistan would be brief, Muslim guerrillas, aided by the US, China, Britain, Saudi Arabia, and Pakistan, waged a fierce resistance against the invasion.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] The Kremlin sent nearly 100,000 troops to support its puppet regime in Afghanistan, leading many outside observers to dub the war "the Soviets' Vietnam".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p02] However, Moscow's quagmire in Afghanistan was far more disastrous for the Soviets than Vietnam had been for the Americans because the conflict coincided with a period of internal decay and domestic crisis in the Soviet system.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] By the time the comparatively youthful Mikhail Gorbachev became General Secretary in 1985, the Soviet economy was stagnant and faced a sharp fall in foreign currency earnings as a result of the downward slide in oil prices in the 1980s.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] These issues prompted Gorbachev to investigate measures to revive the ailing state.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] An ineffectual start led to the conclusion that deeper structural changes were necessary, and in June 1987 Gorbachev announced an agenda of economic reform called *perestroika*, or restructuring.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Perestroika relaxed the production quota system, allowed cooperative ownership of small businesses and paved the way for foreign investment.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] These measures were intended to redirect the country's resources from costly Cold War military commitments to more productive areas in the civilian sector.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Despite initial skepticism in the West, the new Soviet leader proved to be committed to reversing the Soviet Union's deteriorating economic condition instead of continuing the arms race with the West.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Partly as a way to fight off internal opposition from party cliques to his reforms, Gorbachev simultaneously introduced *glasnost*, or openness, which increased freedom of the press and the transparency of state institutions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] *Glasnost* was intended to reduce the corruption at the top of the Communist Party and moderate the abuse of power in the Central Committee.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Glasnost also enabled increased contact between Soviet citizens and the Western world, particularly with the United States, contributing to the accelerating détente between the two nations.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In response to the Kremlin's military and political concessions, Reagan agreed to renew talks on economic issues and the scaling-back of the arms race.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The first summit was held in November 1985 in Geneva, Switzerland.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] A second summit was held in October 1986 in Reykjavík, Iceland.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Talks went well until the focus shifted to Reagan's proposed Strategic Defense Initiative (SDI), which Gorbachev wanted to be eliminated.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The negotiations failed, but the third summit (Washington Summit (1987), 8–10 December 1987) led to a breakthrough with the signing of the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty (INF).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The INF treaty eliminated all nuclear-armed, ground-launched ballistic and cruise missiles with ranges between 500 and 5,500 kilometers (310 and 3,420 mi) and their infrastructure.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] During 1988, it became apparent to the Soviets that oil and gas subsidies, along with the cost of maintaining massive troops levels, represented a substantial economic drain.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In addition, the security advantage of a buffer zone was recognized as irrelevant and the Soviets officially declared that they would no longer intervene in the affairs of satellite states in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Bush and Gorbachev met at the Moscow Summit in May 1988 and the Governors Island Summit in December 1988.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In 1989, Soviet forces withdrew from Afghanistan without achieving their objectives.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Later that year, the Berlin Wall, the Inner German border and the Iron Curtain fell.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] On 3 December 1989, Gorbachev and Bush declared the Cold War over at the Malta Summit.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In February 1990, Gorbachev agreed with the US-proposed Treaty on the Final Settlement with Respect to Germany and signed it on 12 September 1990, paving the way for the German reunification.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] When the Berlin Wall came down, Gorbachev's "Common European Home" concept began to take shape.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The two former adversaries were partners in the Gulf War against Iraq (August 1990 – February 1991).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] During the final summit in Moscow in July 1991, Gorbachev and Bush signed the START I arms control treaty.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Two developments dominated the decade that followed: the increasingly apparent crumbling of the Soviet Union's economic and political structures, and the patchwork attempts at reforms to reverse that process.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Deffeyes argued in *Beyond Oil* that the Reagan administration encouraged Saudi Arabia to lower the price of oil to the point where the Soviets could not make a profit selling their oil, and resulted in the depletion of the country's hard currency reserves.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Brezhnev's next two successors, transitional figures with deep roots in his tradition, did not last long.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Yuri Andropov was 68 years old and Konstantin Chernenko 72 when they assumed power; both died in less than two years.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In an attempt to avoid a third short-lived leader, in 1985, the Soviets turned to the next generation and selected Mikhail Gorbachev.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] He made significant changes in the economy and party leadership, called *perestroika*.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] His policy of *glasnost* freed public access to information after decades of heavy government censorship.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Gorbachev also moved to end the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In 1988, the USSR abandoned its war in Afghanistan and began to withdraw its forces.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In the following year, Gorbachev refused to interfere in the internal affairs of the Soviet satellite states, which paved the way for the Revolutions of 1989.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In particular, the standstill of the Soviet Union at the Pan-European Picnic in August 1989 then set a peaceful chain reaction in motion, at the end of which the Eastern Bloc collapsed.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] With the tearing down of the Berlin Wall and with East and West Germany pursuing re-unification, the Iron Curtain between the West and Soviet-occupied regions came down.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] By 1989, the Soviet alliance system was on the brink of collapse, and, deprived of Soviet military support, the communist leaders of the Warsaw Pact states were losing power.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Grassroots organizations, such as Poland's Solidarity movement, rapidly gained ground with strong popular bases.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The Pan-European Picnic in August 1989 in Hungary finally started a peaceful movement that the rulers in the Eastern Bloc could not stop.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] It was the largest movement of refugees from East Germany since the Berlin Wall was built in 1961 and ultimately brought about the fall of the Iron Curtain.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The patrons of the picnic, Otto von Habsburg and the Hungarian Minister of State Imre Pozsgay, saw the planned event as an opportunity to test Mikhail Gorbachev's reaction.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The Austrian branch of the Paneuropean Union, which was then headed by Otto von Habsburg, distributed thousands of brochures inviting the GDR holidaymakers in Hungary to a picnic near the border at Sopron.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] But with the mass exodus at the Pan-European Picnic the subsequent hesitant behavior of the ruling Socialist Unity Party of East Germany and the non-interference of the Soviet Union broke the dams.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Now tens of thousands of media-informed East Germans made their way to Hungary, which was no longer willing to keep its borders completely closed or to oblige its border troops to use armed force.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] On the one hand, this caused disagreement among the Eastern European states and, on the other hand, it was clear to the Eastern European population that the governments no longer had absolute power.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In 1989, the communist governments in Poland and Hungary became the first to negotiate the organization of competitive elections.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In Czechoslovakia and East Germany, mass protests unseated entrenched communist leaders.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The communist regimes in Bulgaria and Romania also crumbled, in the latter case as the result of a violent uprising.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Attitudes had changed enough that US Secretary of State James Baker suggested that the American government would not be opposed to Soviet intervention in Romania, on behalf of the opposition, to prevent bloodshed.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The tidal wave of change culminated with the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989, which symbolized the collapse of European communist governments and graphically ended the Iron Curtain divide of Europe.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] At the same time, the Soviet republics started legal moves towards potentially declaring sovereignty over their territories, citing the freedom to secede in Article 72 of the USSR constitution.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] On 7 April 1990, a law was passed allowing a republic to secede if more than two-thirds of its residents voted for it in a referendum.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Many held their first free elections in the Soviet era for their own national legislatures in 1990.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Many of these legislatures proceeded to produce legislation contradicting the Union laws in what was known as the 'War of Laws'.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In 1989, the Russian SFSR convened a newly elected Congress of People's Deputies.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] On 12 June 1990, the Congress declared Russia's sovereignty over its territory and proceeded to pass laws that attempted to supersede some of the Soviet laws.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] After a landslide victory of Sąjūdis in Lithuania, that country declared its independence restored on 11 March 1990, citing the illegality of the Soviet occupation of the Baltic states.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Soviet forces attempted to halt the secession by crushing popular demonstrations in Lithuania (Bloody Sunday) and Latvia (The Barricades), as a result, numerous civilians were killed or wounded.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] However, these actions only bolstered international support for the secessionists.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] A referendum for the preservation of the USSR was held on 17 March 1991 in nine republics (the remainder having boycotted the vote), with the majority of the population in those republics voting for preservation of the Union in the form of a new federation.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The referendum gave Gorbachev a minor boost.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In the summer of 1991, the New Union Treaty, which would have turned the country into a much looser Union, was agreed upon by eight republics.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The signing of the treaty, however, was interrupted by the August Coup—an attempted coup d'état by hardline members of the government and the KGB who sought to reverse Gorbachev's reforms and reassert the central government's control over the republics.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] After the coup collapsed, Russian president Yeltsin was seen as a hero for his decisive actions, while Gorbachev's power was effectively ended.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The balance of power tipped significantly towards the republics.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In August 1991, Latvia and Estonia immediately declared the restoration of their full independence (following Lithuania's 1990 example).
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Gorbachev resigned as general secretary in late August, and soon afterwards, the party's activities were indefinitely suspended—effectively ending its rule.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] By the fall, Gorbachev could no longer influence events outside Moscow, and he was being challenged even there by Yeltsin, who had been elected President of Russia in July 1991.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Later in August, Gorbachev resigned as general secretary of the Communist party, and Russian President Boris Yeltsin ordered the seizure of Soviet property.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Gorbachev clung to power as the President of the Soviet Union until 25 December 1991, when the USSR dissolved.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] As such, Russia assumed the Soviet Union's UN membership and permanent membership on the Security Council, nuclear stockpile and the control over the armed forces.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In his 1992 State of the Union Address, US President George H.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Bush expressed his emotions: "The biggest thing that has happened in the world in my life, in our lives, is this: By the grace of God, America won the Cold War." Bush and Yeltsin met in February 1992, declaring a new era of "friendship and partnership".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In January 1993, Bush and Yeltsin agreed to START II, which provided for further nuclear arms reductions on top of the original START treaty.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] According to Western analysis, the neoliberal reforms in Russia culminated in a recession in the early 1990s more severe than the Great Depression as experienced by the United States and Germany.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Stephen Holmes of the University of Chicago argued in 1996 that decommunization, after a brief active period, quickly ended in near-universal failure.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] After the introduction of lustration, demand for scapegoats has become relatively low, and former communists have been elected for high governmental and other administrative positions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Holmes notes that the only real exception was former East Germany, where thousands of former Stasi informers have been fired from public positions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Compared with the decommunization efforts of the other former constituents of the Eastern Bloc and the Soviet Union, decommunization in Russia has been restricted to half-measures, if conducted at all.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Even though Leningrad and Sverdlovsk were renamed, regions that were named after them are still officially called Leningrad and Sverdlovsk oblasts.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Nostalgia for the Soviet Union is gradually on the rise in Russia.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Communist symbols continue to form an important part of the rhetoric used in state-controlled media, as banning on them in other countries is seen by the Russian foreign ministry as "sacrilege" and "a perverse idea of good and evil".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The process of decommunization in Ukraine, a neighbouring post-Soviet state, was met with fierce criticism by Russia.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The State Anthem of the Russian Federation, adopted in 2000 (the same year Vladimir Putin began his first term as president of Russia), uses the exact same music as the State Anthem of the Soviet Union, but with new lyrics written by Sergey Mikhalkov.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Conversely, decommunization in Ukraine started during and after the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] With the success of the Revolution of Dignity in 2014, the Ukrainian government approved laws that outlawed communist symbols.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In July 2015, President of Ukraine Petro Poroshenko signed a set of laws that started a six-month period for the removal of communist monuments (excluding World War II monuments) and renaming of public places named after communist-related themes.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] At the time, this meant that 22 cities and 44 villages were set to get new names.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In 2016, 51,493 streets and 987 cities and villages were renamed, and 1,320 Lenin monuments and 1,069 monuments to other communist figures removed.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Violation of the law carries a penalty of a potential media ban and prison sentences of up to five years.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] By 16 December 2015, these three parties had been banned in Ukraine; the Communist Party of Ukraine appealed the ban to the European Court of Human Rights.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The Cold War had provided external stabilizing pressures.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Both the United States and the Soviet Union had a vested interest in Yugoslavia's stability, ensuring it remained a buffer state in the east–west divide.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] This resulted in financial and political support for its regime.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] When the Cold War ended, this external support evaporated, leaving Yugoslavia more vulnerable to internal divisions.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] As Yugoslavia fragmented, the wars began after Slovenia and Croatia declared independence in 1991.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Serbia, under Slobodan Milošević, opposed these moves.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The Bosnian War (1992–1995) was the most brutal of the Yugoslav Wars, characterized by ethnic cleansing and genocide.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] International organizations, including the United Nations, struggled to manage the violence.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] NATO eventually intervened with airstrikes in Bosnia (1995) as part of Operation Deliberate Force and later in Kosovo (1999) as part of Operation Allied Force.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] These interventions marked the transition of NATO as a deterrent to the Soviet Union, to also functioning at the time as an active peacekeeping and conflict-resolution force.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The post-Cold War world is considered to be unipolar, with the United States the sole remaining superpower.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The Cold War also marked the zenith of peacetime military–industrial complexes and large-scale military funding of science.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Cumulative US military expenditures throughout the entire Cold War amounted to an estimated $8 trillion.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Nearly 100,000 Americans died in the Korean and Vietnam Wars.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Although Soviet casualties are difficult to estimate, as a share of gross national product the financial cost for the Soviet Union was much higher than that incurred by the United States.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Millions died in the superpowers' proxy wars around the globe, most notably in eastern Asia.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Most of the proxy wars and subsidies for local conflicts ended along with the Cold War; interstate wars, ethnic wars, revolutionary wars, as well as refugee and displaced persons crises have declined sharply in the post-Cold War years.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The aftermath of the Cold War is, however, not considered to be concluded.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Many of the economic and social tensions that were exploited to fuel Cold War competition in parts of the Third World remain acute.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The breakdown of state control in a number of areas formerly ruled by communist governments produced new civil and ethnic conflicts, particularly in the former Yugoslavia.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In Central and Eastern Europe, the end of the Cold War has ushered in an era of economic growth and an increase in the number of liberal democracies, while in other parts of the world, such as Afghanistan, independence was accompanied by state failure.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] It has been posited by several scholars that the dissolution of the Soviet Union and the end of communism as a global force in the post-Cold War era allowed neoliberal capitalism to become the dominant global system, which has resulted in rising economic inequality.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] The Cold War endures as a popular topic reflected in entertainment media, and continuing to the present with Cold War-themed feature films, novels, television and web series, and other media.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Interpreting the course and origins of the conflict has been a source of heated controversy among historians, political scientists, and journalists.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] In particular, historians have sharply disagreed as to who was responsible for the breakdown of Soviet–US relations after the Second World War; and whether the conflict between the two superpowers was inevitable or could have been avoided.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Historians have also disagreed on what exactly the Cold War was, what the sources of the conflict were, and how to disentangle patterns of action and reaction between the two sides.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Although explanations of the origins of the conflict in academic discussions are complex and diverse, several general schools of thought on the subject can be identified.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Historians commonly speak of three different approaches to the study of the Cold War: "orthodox" accounts, "revisionism", and "post-revisionism".
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] "Orthodox" accounts place responsibility for the Cold War on the Soviet Union and its expansion further into Europe.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] "Revisionist" writers place more responsibility for the breakdown of post-war peace on the United States, citing a range of US efforts to isolate and confront the Soviet Union well before the end of World War II.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] "Post-revisionists" see the events of the Cold War as more nuanced and attempt to be more balanced in determining what occurred during the Cold War.
[src:big-science/cold-war-p03] Much of the historiography on the Cold War weaves together two or even all three of these broad categories.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] In physics, **cryogenics** is the production and behaviour of materials at very low temperatures.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] This is a logical dividing line, since the normal boiling points of the so-called permanent gases (such as helium, hydrogen, neon, nitrogen, oxygen, and normal air) lie below 120 K, while the Freon refrigerants, hydrocarbons, and other common refrigerants have boiling points above 120 K.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Discovery of superconducting materials with critical temperatures significantly above the boiling point of nitrogen has provided new interest in reliable, low-cost methods of producing high-temperature cryogenic refrigeration.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The term "high temperature cryogenic" describes temperatures ranging from above the boiling point of liquid nitrogen, −195.79 °C (77.36 K; −320.42 °F), up to −50 °C (223 K; −58 °F).
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The discovery of superconductive properties is first attributed to Heike Kamerlingh Onnes on 10 July 1908, after they were able to reach a temperature of 2 K.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] These first superconductive properties were observed in mercury at a temperature of 4.2 K.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The branches of engineering that involve the study of very low temperatures (ultra low temperature i.e. below 123 K), how to produce them, and how materials behave at those temperatures.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The branch of biology involving the study of the effects of low temperatures on organisms (most often for the purpose of achieving cryopreservation).
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Other applications include Lyophilization (freeze-drying) of pharmaceutical components and medicine.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The conservation of genetic material with the intention of conserving a breed.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The conservation of genetic material is not limited to non-humans.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Many services provide genetic storage or the preservation of stem cells at birth.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] They may be used to study the generation of cell lines or for stem-cell therapy.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The branch of surgery applying cryogenic temperatures to destroy and kill tissue, e.g. cancer cells, commonly referred to as cryoablation.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The study of electronic phenomena at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Examples include superconductivity and variable-range hopping.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Cryopreserving humans and animals with the intention of future revival.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] "Cryogenics" is sometimes erroneously used to mean "cryonics" in popular culture and the press.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The word *cryogenics* stems from Greek *κρύος (cryos)* – "cold" + *γενής (genis)* – "generating".
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Cryogenic fluids with their boiling point in Kelvin and degree Celsius.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Liquefied gases, such as liquid nitrogen and liquid helium, are used in many cryogenic applications.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Liquid nitrogen is the most commonly used element in cryogenics and is legally purchasable around the world.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Liquid helium is also commonly used and allows for the lowest attainable temperatures to be reached.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] These liquids may be stored in Dewar flasks, which are double-walled containers with a high vacuum between the walls to reduce heat transfer into the liquid.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Typical laboratory Dewar flasks are spherical, made of glass and protected in a metal outer container.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Dewar flasks for extremely cold liquids such as liquid helium have another double-walled container filled with liquid nitrogen.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Dewar flasks are named after their inventor, James Dewar, the man who first liquefied hydrogen.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Thermos bottles are smaller vacuum flasks fitted in a protective casing.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Cryogenic barcode labels are used to mark Dewar flasks containing these liquids, and will not frost over down to −195 degrees Celsius.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Cryogenic transfer pumps are the pumps used on LNG piers to transfer liquefied natural gas from LNG carriers to LNG storage tanks, as are cryogenic valves.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The field of cryogenics advanced during World War II when scientists found that metals frozen to low temperatures showed more resistance to wear.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Based on this theory of cryogenic hardening, the commercial cryogenic processing industry was founded in 1966 by Bill and Ed Busch.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] With a background in the heat treating industry, the Busch brothers founded a company in Detroit called CryoTech in 1966.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Busch originally experimented with the possibility of increasing the life of metal tools to anywhere between 200% and 400% of the original life expectancy using cryogenic tempering instead of heat treating.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] This evolved in the late 1990s into the treatment of other parts.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Cryogens, such as liquid nitrogen, are further used for specialty chilling and freezing applications.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Some chemical reactions, like those used to produce the active ingredients for the popular statin drugs, must occur at low temperatures of approximately −100 °C (−148 °F).
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Special cryogenic chemical reactors are used to remove reaction heat and provide a low temperature environment.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The freezing of foods and biotechnology products, like vaccines, requires nitrogen in blast freezing or immersion freezing systems.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Certain soft or elastic materials become hard and brittle at very low temperatures, which makes cryogenic milling (cryomilling) an option for some materials that cannot easily be milled at higher temperatures.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Cryogenic processing is not a substitute for heat treatment, but rather an extension of the heating–quenching–tempering cycle.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Normally, when an item is quenched, the final temperature is ambient.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The only reason for this is that most heat treaters do not have cooling equipment.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] There is nothing metallurgically significant about ambient temperature.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The cryogenic process continues this action from ambient temperature down to −320 °F (140 °R; 78 K; −196 °C).
[src:big-science/cryogenics] In most instances the cryogenic cycle is followed by a heat tempering procedure.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] As all alloys do not have the same chemical constituents, the tempering procedure varies according to the material's chemical composition, thermal history and/or a tool's particular service application.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Another use of cryogenics is cryogenic fuels for rockets with liquid hydrogen as the most widely used example, with liquid methane starting to become more prevalent in recent years.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Liquid oxygen (LOX) is even more widely used but as an oxidizer, not a fuel.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] NASA's workhorse Space Shuttle used cryogenic hydrogen/oxygen propellant as its primary means of getting into orbit.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] LOX is also widely used with RP-1 kerosene, a non-cryogenic hydrocarbon, such as in the rockets built for the Soviet space program by Sergei Korolev.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Russian aircraft manufacturer Tupolev developed a version of its popular design Tu-154 with a cryogenic fuel system, known as the Tu-155.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The plane uses a fuel referred to as liquefied natural gas or LNG, and made its first flight in 1989.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Cryogenic cooling of devices and material is usually achieved via the use of liquid nitrogen, liquid helium, or a mechanical cryocooler (which uses high-pressure helium lines).
[src:big-science/cryogenics] Gifford-McMahon cryocoolers, pulse tube cryocoolers and Stirling cryocoolers are in wide use with selection based on required base temperature and cooling capacity.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] The most recent development in cryogenics is the use of magnets as regenerators as well as refrigerators.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] These devices work on the principle known as the magnetocaloric effect.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] There are various cryogenic detectors which are used to detect particles.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] For cryogenic temperature measurement down to 30 K, Pt100 sensors, a resistance temperature detector (RTD), are used.
[src:big-science/cryogenics] For temperatures lower than 30 K, it is necessary to use a silicon diode for accuracy.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] A **cyclotron** is a type of particle accelerator invented by Ernest Lawrence in 1929–1930 at the University of California, Berkeley, and patented in 1932.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] A cyclotron accelerates charged particles outwards from the center of a flat cylindrical vacuum chamber along a spiral path.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] The particles are held to a spiral trajectory by a static magnetic field and accelerated by a rapidly varying electric field.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] Lawrence was awarded the 1939 Nobel Prize in Physics for this invention.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] The cyclotron was the first "cyclical" accelerator.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] The primary accelerators before the development of the cyclotron were electrostatic accelerators, such as the Cockcroft–Walton generator and the Van de Graaff generator.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] In these accelerators, particles would cross an accelerating electric field only once.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] Thus, the energy gained by the particles was limited by the maximum electrical potential that could be achieved across the accelerating region.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] This potential was in turn limited by electrostatic breakdown to a few million volts.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] In a cyclotron, by contrast, the particles encounter the accelerating region many times by following a spiral path, so the output energy can be many times the energy gained in a single accelerating step.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] Cyclotrons were the most powerful particle accelerator technology until the 1950s, when they were surpassed by the synchrotron.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] Nonetheless, they are still widely used to produce particle beams for nuclear medicine and basic research.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] As of 2020, close to 1,500 cyclotrons were in use worldwide for the production of radionuclides for nuclear medicine and ultimately, for the production of radiopharmaceuticals.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] In addition, cyclotrons can be used for particle therapy, where particle beams are directly applied to patients.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] A key limitation of the earliest charged particle accelerators was that increasing the particle energy required extending the length of the acceleration path, which was only feasible and practical up to a certain point.
[src:big-science/cyclotron] In 1927, while a student at Kiel, German physicist Max Steenbeck was the first to formulate the concept of the cyclotron, but he was discouraged from pursuing the idea further.
